"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524475","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-06-17","<p>It is the Government’s position that, wherever possible, prisoners should serve their sentences in their home countries, reducing the burden on the UK taxpayer. A number of factors are taken into account when deciding whether to remove foreign national offenders to serve the remainder of their sentence abroad, including the wishes of victims or their representatives. It is our normal practice to inform victims of the possibility of the transfer of an individual and to give them the opportunity to make their views known.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-06-17T12:44:41.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524475/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524475/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524475/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-06-10","Prisoners: Repatriation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how the wishes of victims of a crime perpetrated by a foreign national offender are taken into account when considering whether to deport that offender to a foreign prison.","false","Biography information for Alec Shelbrooke","Elmet and Rothwell","Alec Shelbrooke","40202"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524476","Scotland Office","false","2016-06-16","<p>I have had a range of discussions with the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, and Scottish Government ministers.</p><p> </p><p>The UK-wide Intellectual Property Office works with law enforcement and industry partners across Scotland to reduce the availability of all types of counterfeits, including electrical goods.</p><p> </p><p>Recent successful joint-enforcement activity involving the Intellectual Property Office, Trading Standards, and Police Scotland, in the Barras Market area of Glasgow, achieved over £30 million pounds worth of fake goods seized. These items included not only counterfeit electrical goods, but fake eBooks, watches, clothing, footwear, and tobacco products.</p><p> </p><p>The operation saw the arrest of 100 traders, the removal of stalls selling fake goods and the return of legitimate business to the area, and is a superb example of the collective effort of Scotland’s two Governments using our powers and potential in a common endeavour.</p><p> </p><p>The Government does not hold data estimating the number of counterfeit electrical goods that were sold in Scotland during the last 12 months. However, we have recently launched a landmark Intellectual Property enforcement strategy in which we have set out how we will improve our data collection. The Intellectual Property Office are developing a robust methodology for measuring the harm caused by IP infringement and a comprehensive scoreboard to be published annually. This will mean better reporting in the criminal justice system, better reporting of court cases, and a deeper understanding of consumer behaviours and emerging trends.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell","40266 ; 40267","2016-06-16T10:42:47.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524476/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524476/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524476/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-06-10","Counterfeit Manufacturing: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what discussions he has had with the Scottish Government on steps to prevent consumers purchasing counterfeit electrical goods that are being sold in Scotland.","false","Biography information for Martin Docherty-Hughes","West Dunbartonshire","Martin Docherty-Hughes","40265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524477","Scotland Office","false","2016-06-16","<p>I have had a range of discussions with the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, and Scottish Government ministers.</p><p> </p><p>The UK-wide Intellectual Property Office works with law enforcement and industry partners across Scotland to reduce the availability of all types of counterfeits, including electrical goods.</p><p> </p><p>Recent successful joint-enforcement activity involving the Intellectual Property Office, Trading Standards, and Police Scotland, in the Barras Market area of Glasgow, achieved over £30 million pounds worth of fake goods seized. These items included not only counterfeit electrical goods, but fake eBooks, watches, clothing, footwear, and tobacco products.</p><p> </p><p>The operation saw the arrest of 100 traders, the removal of stalls selling fake goods and the return of legitimate business to the area, and is a superb example of the collective effort of Scotland’s two Governments using our powers and potential in a common endeavour.</p><p> </p><p>The Government does not hold data estimating the number of counterfeit electrical goods that were sold in Scotland during the last 12 months. However, we have recently launched a landmark Intellectual Property enforcement strategy in which we have set out how we will improve our data collection. The Intellectual Property Office are developing a robust methodology for measuring the harm caused by IP infringement and a comprehensive scoreboard to be published annually. This will mean better reporting in the criminal justice system, better reporting of court cases, and a deeper understanding of consumer behaviours and emerging trends.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell","40265 ; 40266","2016-06-16T10:42:47.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524477/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524477/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524477/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-06-10","Counterfeit Manufacturing: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what estimate he has made of the number of counterfeit electrical goods sold in Scotland in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Martin Docherty-Hughes","West Dunbartonshire","Martin Docherty-Hughes","40267"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524478","Scotland Office","false","2016-06-16","<p>I have had a range of discussions with the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, and Scottish Government ministers.</p><p> </p><p>The UK-wide Intellectual Property Office works with law enforcement and industry partners across Scotland to reduce the availability of all types of counterfeits, including electrical goods.</p><p> </p><p>Recent successful joint-enforcement activity involving the Intellectual Property Office, Trading Standards, and Police Scotland, in the Barras Market area of Glasgow, achieved over £30 million pounds worth of fake goods seized. These items included not only counterfeit electrical goods, but fake eBooks, watches, clothing, footwear, and tobacco products.</p><p> </p><p>The operation saw the arrest of 100 traders, the removal of stalls selling fake goods and the return of legitimate business to the area, and is a superb example of the collective effort of Scotland’s two Governments using our powers and potential in a common endeavour.</p><p> </p><p>The Government does not hold data estimating the number of counterfeit electrical goods that were sold in Scotland during the last 12 months. However, we have recently launched a landmark Intellectual Property enforcement strategy in which we have set out how we will improve our data collection. The Intellectual Property Office are developing a robust methodology for measuring the harm caused by IP infringement and a comprehensive scoreboard to be published annually. This will mean better reporting in the criminal justice system, better reporting of court cases, and a deeper understanding of consumer behaviours and emerging trends.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell","40265 ; 40267","2016-06-16T10:42:47.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524478/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524478/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524478/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-06-10","Counterfeit Manufacturing: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills on steps to prevent counterfeit electrical goods from being sold in Scotland.","false","Biography information for Martin Docherty-Hughes","West Dunbartonshire","Martin Docherty-Hughes","40266"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524479","Department for Transport","false","2016-06-15","<p>HS2 Ltd and the Department for Transport have been analysing route and station options in light of responses received following the Phase Two consultation. It would not be appropriate to go into detail on any individual location before a route decision has been taken. A route decision is planned for autumn 2016.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-06-15T15:26:03.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524479/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524479/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524479/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-06-10","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will re-assess the business case for the Hoo Green to Bamfurlong spur of the second phase of High Speed 2 to take account of the decision to place the train depot at Crewe rather than Golborne.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","40242"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524480","Department for Transport","false","2016-06-15","<p>The Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA) deals with more than 600,000 medical driver licensing applications annually. The length of time taken to deal with an individual application depends on the medical condition and whether further information is required from medical professionals.</p><p> </p><p>For the period April 2015 to March 2016, the average time for an assessment and a licensing decision to be made was 53 working days, irrespective of age. Between April 2014 and March 2015, the figure was 58 working days.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-06-15T10:57:14.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524480/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524480/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524480/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-06-10","Driving: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 6 June 2016 to Question 38478, what the current average time taken is to process driving licence renewal applications for people over 70 years old where medical investigations are required.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","40260"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524481","Department for Transport","false","2016-06-15","<p>The first Road Investment Strategy (RIS) recognises that tackling congestion on the A19 is a priority and includes a scheme to widen the A19 between the A1027 (Norton) and A689 (Wynyard).</p><p> </p><p>In addition, the Tees Valley Combined Authority and the local authorities are working in partnership with Highways England to identify options for a new crossing of the Tees to enhance the road network. The Combined Authority has made a bid to the Department’s Large Majors scheme for 2016/17 to develop proposals. The results of bids into this fund are due to be published in July 2016.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Highways England has begun gathering evidence to support the development of the second RIS period which commences in 2020/21. The evidence from Lord Heseltine’s Report will be taken into account in this process.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-06-15T10:43:22.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524481/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524481/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524481/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-06-10","Bridges: Tees Valley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to paragraph 9.2.7 of the report by Lord Heseltine, Tees Valley: opportunity unlimited, published in June 2016, if he will make it his policy to provide a new strategic road Tees crossing.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","40244"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524482","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-06-14","<p>Data on the number of claims made for personal independence payment (PIP), and the proportion of such claims which were unsuccessful, are available from Stat-Xplore: <a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a>. Guidance on how to use Stat-Xplore can be found here: <a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/index.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/index.html</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Appeals against PIP decisions may be made where an award of benefit has been given or not. Data on appeals is a matter for Her Majesty’s Courts and Tribunals Service, an executive agency sponsored by the Ministry of Justice. The latest available data on appeals can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/tribunals-statistics#social-security-and-child-support-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/tribunals-statistics#social-security-and-child-support-statistics</a>.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-06-14T14:52:59.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524482/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524482/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524482/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-06-10","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many applications there were for personal independence payments in the latest year for which figures are available; what proportion of those applications were rejected; and what proportion of unsuccessful applications were subsequently granted on appeal.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","40246"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524483","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-06-16","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave to his previous Question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-06-08/39987/" target="_blank">UIN39987</a>.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-06-16T14:18:08.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524483/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524483/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524483/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-06-10","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when his Department plans to publish the findings of its forthcoming review on personal independence payments.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","40247"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524484","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-06-20","<p>Mandatory Reconsiderations were introduced in October 2013. There were 1,100 decisions made from October to the end of 2013; 54,100 in 2014; and 18,500 in 2015.</p><p> </p><p>This is the latest data available. The total cost of processing those reconsiderations is not available at the level of detail requested.</p><p> </p><p>These figures are published here <a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a></p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-06-20T08:49:30.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524484/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524484/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524484/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-06-10","Jobseeker's Allowance: Disqualification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many mandatory reconsiderations of jobseekers' allowance sanctions there have been in each of the last five years; and what the total cost was of processing such reconsiderations in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","40205"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524485","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-06-17","<p>Work Programme providers are not paid cash commissions and are not paid for individuals completing the programme. Providers are paid by results on the basis of a job outcome fee for supporting an individual into sustained employment and additional sustainment payments for keeping them in work longer.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-06-17T12:29:51.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524485/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524485/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524485/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-06-10","Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the value was of the cash commission paid to companies for clients' completion of the Work Programme in each year from 2011 to 2016.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","40231"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524486","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-06-15","<p>Bereavement support payments (BSP) will replace both Widowed Parent’s Allowance and Bereavement Allowance for those bereaved from April 2017 onwards.</p><p>BSP will not be taken into account when calculating income for the benefit cap and will also be paid in addition to income related benefits to ensure that the least well off families are financially better off under the reform.</p><p> </p><p>Further information is provided via the link below.</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/311318/pensions-act-ia-annex-d-bereavement-support-payment.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/311318/pensions-act-ia-annex-d-bereavement-support-payment.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-06-15T15:02:47.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524486/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524486/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524486/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-06-10","Bereavement Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the long-term effect on incomes of households with children affected by the planned replacement of widowed parent's allowance by bereavement allowance.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","40218"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524487","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-06-20","<p>The information is not available.</p><p>Where a customer holds an active relationship with DWP either through claiming a Winter Fuel Payment previously or being in receipt of a benefit, such as a state pension, their Winter Fuel Payment is made automatically.</p><p>Claims are required from those where DWP does not hold the data necessary to generate an automatic payment.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-06-20T15:44:44.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524487/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524487/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524487/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-06-10","Winter Fuel Payments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many winter fuel payments were delayed by administrative problems in the last year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","40227"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524489","Department of Health","false","2016-06-15","<p>Public Health England does not plan to revise its campaigns and dietary advice in light of the recent opinion paper published by the National Obesity Forum and the Public Health Collaboration.</p><p> </p><p>Government advice continues to encourage consumption of dairy products as part of a healthy, balanced diet in line with the Eatwell Guide; advising people to choose lower fat varieties of milk and dairy products where possible, due to the evidence that high intakes of saturated fat are associated with raised blood cholesterol and cardiovascular risk.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-06-15T13:40:45.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524489/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524489/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524489/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-10","Local Government: Pay","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the opinion paper by the National Obesity Forum and the Public Health Collaboration <i>Eat Fat, Cut the Carbs and Avoid Snacking to Reverse Obesity and Type 2 Diabetes,</i> whether they plan to revise NHS and Public Health England campaigns that discourage the consumption of dairy products, including full-fat milk, butter, cream and cheese.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL592"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524490","Department of Health","false","2016-06-15","<p>Government advice is that people should base meals on starchy carbohydrates, especially wholegrain; eat at least five portions of a variety of fruit and vegetables each day; and cut back on food and drinks high in saturated fat, salt, sugar and calories.</p><p> </p><p>The Scientific Advisory Committee on Nutrition (SACN) is currently reviewing evidence on saturated fat and health. A draft report is planned for public consultation at the end of 2017. Current advice will remain in place until the SACN has completed its review.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-06-15T13:40:03.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524490/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524490/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524490/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-10","Farms: Public Footpaths","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to (1) review the long-standing advice by the Department of Health against eating fatty foods, and (2) publish revised advice.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL593"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524491","Department of Health","false","2016-06-20","<p>As part of the DH2020 plan, the Department is making significant changes to the way it works. The underlying principles informing the changes include that the Department should focus on its core and unique functions to improve the health and care system in England to help people to live better for longer.</p><p> </p><p>The Department’s approach is to flexibly access professional advice from a wide range of sources, including arms-length bodies, regulators and professional bodies, rather than from fixed standing teams of internal advisers.</p><p>These changes do not affect the role of the Chief Nursing Officer (CNO), who as the CNO of the Department already advises, and will continue to advise, all Ministers and the Department on the range of nursing issues.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-06-20T12:23:34.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524491/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524491/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524491/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-10","Broadband","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to reduce the number of nurse advisers in the Department of Health.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL594"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524492","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-23","<p>The Government will review the outcomes of the independent review of UK Anti-Doping’s processes following allegations made in the Sunday Times. DCMS is currently undertaking a review of current legislation and, as part of this, will consider the independent review’s findings to determine whether any new powers are necessary.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-06-23T13:55:27.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524492/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524492/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524492/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-06-10","Foreign Exchange","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to (1) extend the powers of UK Anti-Doping (UKAD) to investigate doctors administering performance enhancing drugs to athletes outside the control of British governing bodies of sport, and (2) introduce new powers to enable UKAD to take legal action should such doctors be found to have breached the World Anti-Doping Agency Code; and if so, when.","false","Biography information for Lord Moynihan",,"Lord Moynihan","HL595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524493","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-23","<p>The review is expected to conclude during the summer. UK Anti-Doping will publish the report.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-06-23T13:51:34.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524493/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524493/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524493/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-06-10","Atrial Fibrillation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they expect the independent review by Andy Ward into UK Anti-Doping's handling of intelligence in relation to Dr Mark Bonar to be finalised, and whether they intend to lay a copy of that report before Parliament.","false","Biography information for Lord Moynihan",,"Lord Moynihan","HL596"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524494","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-15","<p>The Government has not made an assessment of advice by Europe Direct on this issue.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-06-15T14:48:23.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524494/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524494/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524494/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-10","Atrial Fibrillation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the advice by Europe Direct that providing unique reference numbers on tickets by primary and secondary market ticket sellers is not regulated under the Consumer Rights Directive, and is therefore permitted.","false","Biography information for Lord Moynihan",,"Lord Moynihan","HL597"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524495","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-23","<p>UK Anti-Doping has not been asked to provide 30 days’ notice by Russian authorities. UK Anti-Doping is not involved in the contractual agreement between the Russian Anti-Doping Agency (RUSADA) and sample collection agencies. This would be a matter for RUSADA and the World Anti-Doping Agency. While UK Anti-Doping has encountered challenges due to customs delays, it does not discuss details of its testing programmes as doing so might undermine what it is trying to achieve and the processes involved.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-06-23T13:53:43.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524495/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524495/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524495/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-06-10","Atrial Fibrillation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether, in carrying out its assignment in Russia on behalf of the World Anti-Doping Agency, UK Anti-Doping has at any time (1) been asked for 30 days’ notice of tests by Russian authorities; (2) disputed payments for doping control officers; or (3) faced customs delays preventing the transport of blood samples to laboratories outside Russia within the 48-hour window needed for accurate testing or at any time been unable to match the tests being undertaken by the Russian Anti-Doping Agency to Russian athletes; and if so, on which occasions those events occurred.","false","Biography information for Lord Moynihan",,"Lord Moynihan","HL598"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524496","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-06-21","<p>Prison staff regularly discuss issues relating to radicalisation and extremism with prison chaplains of all faiths, both at a local and regional level. Prisoners who are identified as holding extremist views or being vulnerable to radicalisation are managed through a range of interventions to tackle and disrupt extremist behaviour.</p><p>Last year the Justice Secretary commissioned A review of extremism in prisons</p><p><br> As we have made clear, the report has been received and a summary document will be published in due course.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2016-06-21T13:07:53.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524496/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524496/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524496/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-06-10","Parliament: Broadcasting","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions they are having with prison chaplains, including those of Muslim and Christian faith, to address concerns about radicalisation and extremism in prisons.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of Rochester",,"The Lord Bishop of Rochester","HL599"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524497","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-06-30","<p>Radicalisation is a process rather than an event and therefore it is not possible to identify with any certainty which prisoners have been radicalised specifically during their time in prison.</p><p>Extremism is one of the biggest threats facing this country. That is why the Justice Secretary commissioned a review of Islamist extremism in prisons.</p><p>As we have made clear, the report has been received and a summary document will be published in due course.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2016-06-30T11:38:13.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524497/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524497/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524497/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-06-10","Reserve Forces","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many prisoners have been identified as having been radicalised whilst in custody in England and Wales since the beginning of 2014.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of Rochester",,"The Lord Bishop of Rochester","HL600"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524498","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-21","<p>The European Commission is actively negotiating seven bilateral trade and investment agreements. These are with the following countries: USA, Japan, Philippines, India, the Mercosur bloc, Morocco and Tunisia. The European Commission is negotiating bilateral investment agreements with Burma and China. In addition, the European Commission is also engaged in the negotiation of two “plurilateral” agreements on behalf of the EU: the Trade in Services Agreement and the Environmental Goods Agreement.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Price",,"2016-06-21T13:37:23.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524498/answer","Biography information for Lord Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524498/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524498/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-10","Families: Disadvantaged","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many trade agreements are currently being negotiated by the EU, and with which countries.","false","Biography information for Viscount Waverley",,"Viscount Waverley","HL601"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524499","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-21","<p>The EU-Southern Africa Economic Partnership Agreement and the EU-Central America Association Agreement are expected to be presented to Parliament in the near future.</p><p> </p><p>The EU has concluded negotiations with the following partners and, assuming that these agreements are approved in Council as being of “mixed competence”, each will need to be approved by Parliament: Canada, Ecuador, Singapore, Vietnam, Eastern Africa, and Western Africa.</p>",,"Lord Price",,"2016-06-21T12:48:30.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524499/answer","Biography information for Lord Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524499/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524499/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-10","Child Rearing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government which European trade agreements are awaiting ratification by the UK Parliament.","false","Biography information for Viscount Waverley",,"Viscount Waverley","HL602"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524500","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-23","<p>Before any determination is issued and any payments made under that determination, regulations on the definition of higher value assets must first be passed by both Houses of Parliament. We are currently working on the detail of the regulations.</p><p>We shall consult with local authorities and other stakeholders before issuing the determination.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL604","2016-06-23T14:10:32.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524500/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524500/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524500/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-06-10","Academies: North West","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when the Secretary of State will make a determination under section 69 of the Housing and Planning Act 2016.","false","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham",,"Lord Young of Cookham","HL603"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524501","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-23","<p>Before any determination is issued and any payments made under that determination, regulations on the definition of higher value assets must first be passed by both Houses of Parliament. We are currently working on the detail of the regulations.</p><p>We shall consult with local authorities and other stakeholders before issuing the determination.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL603","2016-06-23T14:10:32.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524501/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524501/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524501/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-06-10","Flood Control: North West","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when local authorities have to make the first payment under section 69 of the Housing and Planning Act 2016.","false","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham",,"Lord Young of Cookham","HL604"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524502","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-23","<p>Section 64 of the Housing and Planning Act 2016 enables the Secretary of State to pay grant to private registered providers to cover the cost of the voluntary Right to Buy discount. Grant will only be paid out once a tenant has purchased their home and the provider has submitted a claim. Systems are in place with the five housing associations that are taking part in the voluntary Right to Buy pilot so that the Government can compensate them for the discount that their tenants get when they purchase their home.</p><p>We are currently working with the National Housing Federation and the housing association sector on the implementation of the main scheme and will announce more details in due course.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-06-23T14:01:26.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524502/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524502/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524502/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-06-10","Representation of the People Act 1918","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when the Secretary of State will commence making grants to private registered providers under section 64 of the Housing and Planning Act 2016.","false","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham",,"Lord Young of Cookham","HL605"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524189","Attorney General","true","2016-06-14","<p>A press release was issued by the Metropolitan Police Service which stated that the complainant was under 16. The CPS was not a party to this release and did not issue any other release. The CPS does not retain records of publicity resulting at the time.</p><p> </p><p>When the case was reviewed in 2014 for charging, the complainant and the witness clearly stated that the complainant had been 15 when the incident took place in 1986.<del class="ministerial"> In addition Mr Virdi also said in interview that the complainant had been 15 at the time of the incident.</del> The police summary stated that the complainant was 15. However the complainant’s date of birth and the date of his arrest were known and this mistake should not have been made.</p><p> </p><p>The CPS was supplied with the memorandum of conviction referred to on 17 September 2014.<del class="ministerial">The indictment was formally amended thereafter.</del></p><p> </p><p>No steps were taken to publicise the fact that the charge was later amended in open court to remove the assertion that the complainant was under 16.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2016-06-14T13:53:54.987Z","2016-06-24T09:44:08.533Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524189/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524189/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524189/answer","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524189/answer/previousversion/3723","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-06-09","Gurpal Virdi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how and why the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) joined the Metropolitan Police in announcing that retired police sergeant Gurpal Virdi was charged with misconduct in public office and with indecent assault on a person under 16 years; what publicity the CPS recorded as resulting at the time; when the memorandum of a conviction proved 1 April 1987 for offences on 7 November 1986 of a defendant born on 5 September 1970 with informant or complainant recorded as PC Markwick came to the attention of the CPS; what steps were taken to put right the effect of the wrong statement; when those steps were taken; and what the results of those steps were.","false","Biography information for Sir Peter Bottomley","Worthing West","Sir Peter Bottomley","40180"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524190","Attorney General","false","2016-06-14","<p>The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) has requested an estimate of the cost of obtaining a transcript and has been informed that it will take 10 days for this to be supplied. Once the estimate is received the CPS will write to the Honorable Member to inform him of the figure.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2016-06-14T13:52:08.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524190/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524190/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524190/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-06-09","Gurpal Virdi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what the cost is to the Crown Prosecution Service of obtaining a transcript of the Southwark Crown Court trial of charges against Gurpal Virdi.","false","Biography information for Sir Peter Bottomley","Worthing West","Sir Peter Bottomley","40181"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524191","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-14","<p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Statistical data broken down by region on (a) apprentices working full-time for the employer with which they trained or (b) were subsequently unemployed, is not available.</p><p> </p><p>Latest Apprenticeship Evaluation Learner Survey 2016 data show that 9 out of 10 of all recent apprenticeship completers were in employment 12-20 months after completion. And 72% of those in employment were with the same employer with whom they completed their apprenticeship.</p><p> </p><p>Information on Apprenticeship starts by region and local authority is published as a supplementary table (first link) to a Statistical First Release (second link).</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/509995/apprenticeships-starts-by-geography-learner-demographics-and-sector-subject-area.XLS" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/509995/apprenticeships-starts-by-geography-learner-demographics-and-sector-subject-area.XLS</a></p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/learner-participation-outcomes-and-level-of-highest-qualification-held" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/learner-participation-outcomes-and-level-of-highest-qualification-held</a></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-06-14T16:08:05.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524191/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524191/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524191/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-09","Apprentices: Tees Valley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what proportion of apprentices in the Tees Valley area (a) went on to work full-time with the employer with which they trained and (b) were subsequently unemployed in the last year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","40117"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524192","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-15","<p>Post Office Limited runs and operates its directly managed Crown post offices. Changes to its network and proposals to franchise of some of its Crown branches are the operational responsibility of the Post Office. The Post Office’s proposals for franchising some of its Crown branches are part of its work to ensure its branch network is sustainable in the long term and ensure that Post Office services remain on our high streets across the country. The change from a Crown to a franchise branch has been undertaken successfully in many locations across the UK and helps sustain Post Office services in these locations, and each change is subject to local consultation.</p><p> </p><p>Over 97% of the UK’s post office network is run on a franchise or agency basis.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","40136","2016-06-15T08:39:17.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524192/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524192/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524192/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-09","Post Offices: Paisley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if his Department will make an assessment of the potential effect on (a) businesses and (b) the local community in Paisley of the decision to close the Post Office branch and replace it with a franchise.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","40139"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524193","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-15","<p>Post Office Limited runs and operates its directly managed Crown post offices. Changes to its network and proposals to franchise of some of its Crown branches are the operational responsibility of the Post Office. The Post Office’s proposals for franchising some of its Crown branches are part of its work to ensure its branch network is sustainable in the long term and ensure that Post Office services remain on our high streets across the country. The change from a Crown to a franchise branch has been undertaken successfully in many locations across the UK and helps sustain Post Office services in these locations, and each change is subject to local consultation.</p><p> </p><p>Over 97% of the UK’s post office network is run on a franchise or agency basis.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","40139","2016-06-15T08:39:17.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524193/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524193/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524193/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-09","Post Offices: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment his Department has made of the effect on (a) businesses and (b) local communities in Scotland of the decision to allow the closure of Post Office branches in Scotland and their replacement by franchises.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","40136"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524194","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-14","<p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The UK Space Agency and the Engineering and Physical Sciences Research Council (EPSRC) follow the Cross-Council Funding Agreement.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-06-14T14:59:13.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524194/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524194/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524194/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-09","Science: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether there is a mechanism equivalent to the Cross-Council Funding Agreement to ensure fair peer review and transparency for research proposals crossing the border between the Engineering and Physical Sciences Research Council and the UK Space Agency.","false","Biography information for Carol Monaghan","Glasgow North West","Carol Monaghan","40096"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524195","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-14","<p>A Government consultation seeking views on options to move Land Registry operations to the private sector closed on 26 May. My department is analysing these responses to help inform a Government decision. The effect on the public purse will also be considered as part of this decision.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-06-14T11:45:37.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524195/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524195/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524195/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-09","Land Registry: Privatisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the effect on the public purse of privatising the Land Registry while maintaining ownership of the Land Register.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","40115"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524196","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-14","<p>Since its launch in October 2012, GOV.UK has handled over 2.6 billion visits. The site needs to continue operating during major events. The <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a> website has been designed to handle issues and failures in a way which would not impact the public. We have robust incident management processes in place and regularly run disaster recovery simulations to test our response to any outages.</p><p>When outages do occur, we investigate and learn lessons on how to mitigate them in future.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","40091","2016-06-14T08:54:28.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524196/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524196/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524196/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-09","Electronic Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what contingency plans the Cabinet Office has in place in the event of a high-volume of users causing a slow-down or failure of the gov.uk website.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","40105"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524197","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-14","<p>GOV.UK does not collect socio-demographic data of users.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-06-14T08:58:10.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524197/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524197/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524197/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-09","Electronic Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment his Department has made of the socio-demographic characteristics of users visiting the gov.uk website.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","40097"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524198","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-15","<p>Over 100,000 people have taken user satisfaction surveys on the <a href="http://h/" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a> website since 2013. The most recent information is as follows;</p><p>On content accuracy, 69.5% they agreed or strongly responded that they “Trust the information on <a href="http://h/" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a>&quot;.</p><p>On the ability to find information, in 2016 52% responded that they agreed or strongly agreed that <a href="http://h/" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a> was “easy to use”, up from 42% in 2015</p><p>On the question of the proportion of users who got everything or most of what they wanted when visiting the website, in 2016 46% responded that they agreed or strongly agreed with this statement up from 36% in 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-06-15T07:43:29.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524198/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524198/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524198/answer","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524198/answer/previousversion/3884","Biography information for Matt Hancock","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-09","Electronic Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the customer satisfaction ratings were for the gov.uk website related to (a) content accuracy, (b) ability to find information, (c) proportion of users who found the website search tool good or very good and (d) proportion of users who got everything or most of what they wanted when visiting the website since 2012.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","40094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524199","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-14","<p>Since its launch in October 2012, GOV.UK has handled over 2.6 billion visits. The site needs to continue operating during major events. The <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a> website has been designed to handle issues and failures in a way which would not impact the public. We have robust incident management processes in place and regularly run disaster recovery simulations to test our response to any outages.</p><p>When outages do occur, we investigate and learn lessons on how to mitigate them in future.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","40105","2016-06-14T08:54:28.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524199/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524199/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524199/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-09","Electronic Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what contingency plans his Department has in place in the event of a failure of all or part of the gov.uk website.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","40091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524200","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-14","<p>The annual running cost of the GOV.UK website between financial year 2012/13 and 2014/15 is available online at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/central-government-websites" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/central-government-websites</a>.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-06-14T09:01:46.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524200/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524200/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524200/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-09","Electronic Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the annual running cost of the gov.uk website was in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","40092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524201","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-14","<p>The EU referendum will be overseen by the Chief Counting Officer, chair of the Electoral Commission, who is responsible for making sure the referendum is held in accordance with the legislation governing the conduct of the poll. The Electoral Commission has issued a statement setting out the actions that have been taken to address an issue with elections software used by a number of local authorities in England and Wales that meant that some non-eligible EU citizens had mistakenly received poll cards and, in some instances, postal votes. The Commission explains that the software provider has resolved the issue and none of the affected electors will be shown as eligible on the electoral registers to be used at polling stations on the 23 June. Any incorrectly issued postal votes will be cancelled.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose","40158 ; 40169 ; 40170","2016-06-14T16:02:13.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524201/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524201/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524201/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-09","UK Membership of EU: Referendums","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps the Government is taking to ensure that those non-UK citizens who are not eligible to vote are not able to vote in the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","40157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524202","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-14","<p>The EU referendum will be overseen by the Chief Counting Officer, chair of the Electoral Commission, who is responsible for making sure the referendum is held in accordance with the legislation governing the conduct of the poll. The Electoral Commission has issued a statement setting out the actions that have been taken to address an issue with elections software used by a number of local authorities in England and Wales that meant that some non-eligible EU citizens had mistakenly received poll cards and, in some instances, postal votes. The Commission explains that the software provider has resolved the issue and none of the affected electors will be shown as eligible on the electoral registers to be used at polling stations on the 23 June. Any incorrectly issued postal votes will be cancelled.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose","40157 ; 40169 ; 40170","2016-06-14T16:02:13.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524202/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524202/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524202/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-09","UK Membership of EU: Referendums","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will request that the Electoral Commission investigate the extent to which the electoral roll prepared for the EU referendum on 23 June 2016 contains citizens of EU countries who are not eligible to vote.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","40158"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524203","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-15","<p>We do not differentiate between ownership of technology and evidence in our assessments of who can use <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a> Verify.</p><p><a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a> Verify works for 90% of working adults in the UK, which is the main user group for most of the services currently using <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a> Verify. Coverage is lower amongst very young people and older people - we continue to improve coverage for those age groups.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-06-15T09:05:24.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524203/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524203/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524203/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-09","Proof of Identity: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate he has made of the proportion of people aged (a) 16 to 24, (b) 25 to 44, (c) 45 to 54, (d) 55 to 64, (e) 65 to 74 and (f) 75 years and older who have the (i) evidence and (ii) technology needed to verify their identity online.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","40125"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524204","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-17","<p>The 2013 cohort for the Fast Stream joined over the course of 6 months between May and October with a final single joiner in December. At April 2016 there were 185 fast streamers on the first cohort of the Corporate Fast Stream Programme, 120 (65% of total) have completed a posting outside of London ‎to date. The Corporate Fast Stream programme lasts 4 years so full data for this cohort will not be available until the end of 2017 when all participants have completed the programme.</p><p>The Fast Stream aspiration is to have 100% of corporately managed Fast Streamers experience at least one posting outside of London during the 4 year scheme.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-06-17T10:28:45.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524204/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524204/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524204/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-09","Civil Servants: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 8 June 2016 to Question 39272, what proportion of the cohort of Civil Service Fast Streamers who joined in April 2013 have already undertaken a regional placement.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","40168"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524205","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-14","<p>The EU referendum will be overseen by the Chief Counting Officer, chair of the Electoral Commission, who is responsible for making sure the referendum is held in accordance with the legislation governing the conduct of the poll. The Electoral Commission has issued a statement setting out the actions that have been taken to address an issue with elections software used by a number of local authorities in England and Wales that meant that some non-eligible EU citizens had mistakenly received poll cards and, in some instances, postal votes. The Commission explains that the software provider has resolved the issue and none of the affected electors will be shown as eligible on the electoral registers to be used at polling stations on the 23 June. Any incorrectly issued postal votes will be cancelled.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose","40157 ; 40158 ; 40170","2016-06-14T16:02:13.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524205/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524205/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524205/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-09","UK Membership of EU: Referendums","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will request that the Electoral Commission investigate the extent to which the electoral roll prepared for the referendum on the UK's membership of the EU 2016 includes citizens of EU countries who are not eligible to vote.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","40169"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524206","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-14","<p>The EU referendum will be overseen by the Chief Counting Officer, chair of the Electoral Commission, who is responsible for making sure the referendum is held in accordance with the legislation governing the conduct of the poll. The Electoral Commission has issued a statement setting out the actions that have been taken to address an issue with elections software used by a number of local authorities in England and Wales that meant that some non-eligible EU citizens had mistakenly received poll cards and, in some instances, postal votes. The Commission explains that the software provider has resolved the issue and none of the affected electors will be shown as eligible on the electoral registers to be used at polling stations on the 23 June. Any incorrectly issued postal votes will be cancelled.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose","40157 ; 40158 ; 40169","2016-06-14T16:02:13.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524206/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524206/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524206/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-09","UK Membership of EU: Referendums","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps the Government is taking to ensure that non-UK citizens who are not eligible to vote are not able to vote in the referendum on the UK's membership of the EU.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","40170"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524207","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-14","<p>When consumer credit regulation transferred from the Office of Fair Trading (OFT) to the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) on 1 April 2014, the Government decided that, given their central role in helping to inform responsible lending decisions, CRAs should be directly regulated by the FCA. As such, every credit reference agency’s fitness to trade is being assessed as part of the FCA’s robust authorisation process</p><p> </p><p>Information on a credit report should be purely factual; for example, if arrears were incurred, those lenders who share data through the credit reference agencies will have recorded them.</p><p> </p><p>A credit reference agency is able to correct factually inaccurate information. However, it is the original lender or organisation that supplies credit to a consumer that provides the agencies with the information held on a credit report. Where inaccurate information has been reported to a credit reference agency, a consumer must contact the lender in the first instance.</p><p> </p><p>If a problem with inaccurate data is not resolved satisfactorily with a lender, consumers are able to complain to the Information Commissioner’s Office (ICO), which is able to investigate and take action where necessary. The ICO is the UK's independent body set up to uphold information rights, and it enforces the Data Protection Act.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","40184 ; 40186","2016-06-14T15:42:06.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524207/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524207/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524207/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-09","Credit Reference Agencies: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make an estimate of the level of accuracy of the credit records held by credit reporting agencies; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","40182"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524208","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-14","<p>Treasury Ministers and officials meet with a wide range of companies and organisations to discuss relevant issues.</p><p> </p><p>Details of ministerial meetings with external organisations on departmental business are published on a quarterly basis and are available at: https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-ministers-meetings-hospitality-gifts-and-overseas-travel</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-06-14T15:38:48.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524208/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524208/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524208/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-09","Credit Reference Agencies: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when Ministers or senior officials of his Department last met with credit ratings agencies to discuss the accuracy of the credit record histories of UK nationals; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","40183"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524209","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-14","<p>When consumer credit regulation transferred from the Office of Fair Trading (OFT) to the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) on 1 April 2014, the Government decided that, given their central role in helping to inform responsible lending decisions, CRAs should be directly regulated by the FCA. As such, every credit reference agency’s fitness to trade is being assessed as part of the FCA’s robust authorisation process</p><p> </p><p>Information on a credit report should be purely factual; for example, if arrears were incurred, those lenders who share data through the credit reference agencies will have recorded them.</p><p> </p><p>A credit reference agency is able to correct factually inaccurate information. However, it is the original lender or organisation that supplies credit to a consumer that provides the agencies with the information held on a credit report. Where inaccurate information has been reported to a credit reference agency, a consumer must contact the lender in the first instance.</p><p> </p><p>If a problem with inaccurate data is not resolved satisfactorily with a lender, consumers are able to complain to the Information Commissioner’s Office (ICO), which is able to investigate and take action where necessary. The ICO is the UK's independent body set up to uphold information rights, and it enforces the Data Protection Act.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","40182 ; 40186","2016-06-14T15:42:06.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524209/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524209/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524209/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-09","Credit Reference Agencies: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make it his policy to require regular audits of the accuracy of records held by credit ratings agencies on UK nationals' credit history; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","40184"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524210","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-14","<p>This question has been passed on to the FCA. The FCA will reply to directly to the Honourable member by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-06-14T15:40:18.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524210/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524210/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524210/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-09","Credit Reference Agencies: Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many fines have been levied on credit rating agencies (a) in total and (b) for inaccurate reports of individuals' credit records; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","40185"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524211","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-14","<p>When consumer credit regulation transferred from the Office of Fair Trading (OFT) to the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) on 1 April 2014, the Government decided that, given their central role in helping to inform responsible lending decisions, CRAs should be directly regulated by the FCA. As such, every credit reference agency’s fitness to trade is being assessed as part of the FCA’s robust authorisation process</p><p> </p><p>Information on a credit report should be purely factual; for example, if arrears were incurred, those lenders who share data through the credit reference agencies will have recorded them.</p><p> </p><p>A credit reference agency is able to correct factually inaccurate information. However, it is the original lender or organisation that supplies credit to a consumer that provides the agencies with the information held on a credit report. Where inaccurate information has been reported to a credit reference agency, a consumer must contact the lender in the first instance.</p><p> </p><p>If a problem with inaccurate data is not resolved satisfactorily with a lender, consumers are able to complain to the Information Commissioner’s Office (ICO), which is able to investigate and take action where necessary. The ICO is the UK's independent body set up to uphold information rights, and it enforces the Data Protection Act.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","40182 ; 40184","2016-06-14T15:42:06.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524211/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524211/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524211/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-09","Credit Reference Agencies: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will take steps to require the Financial Conduct Authority to require credit rating agencies to improve their reporting of an individual's credit record; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","40186"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524212","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-14","<p>I welcome Lord Heseltine’s independent report on the Tees Valley following the closure of the SSI steelworks. As noted in the report, the Government is providing funding for an intermediate body to manage the site prior to the creation of the Mayoral Development Corporation, and is funding site assessments in 2016-17 in order to understand the scale and complexity of the SSI site. The case for any further Government funding will be considered in light of those assessments.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-06-14T16:12:25.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524212/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524212/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524212/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-09","Sahaviriya Steel Industries UK: Redcar","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether his Department plans to provide any funding for a further assessment of the Redcar SSI site as recommended in the independent report, Tees Valley: opportunity unlimited, published on 7 June 2016.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","40128"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524213","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-15","<p>The document entitled<em> HM Treasury analysis: the immediate economic impact of leaving the EU </em>provides more detail on the impact that leaving the EU would have on GDP, CPI inflation and on average real wages, in Section 2, Part 3 of the document.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, the Treasury has published further analysis of the impact that leaving the EU would have on pensioner incomes in <em>Effects on pensioners from leaving the EU</em>. Details on the effect on the value of State Pension and the triple lock are included in the section entitled <em>Effects on pensioner incomes</em> on pages 2-3.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-06-15T16:07:30.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524213/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524213/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524213/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-09","State Retirement Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the Answer of 24 May 2016 to Question 37689, if he will indicate where in that document details are provided on the (a) potential effect on the triple lock pension policy and (b) value of state pensions for people who retire before 6 April 2016 of a potential reduction in economic growth in the event of the UK voting to leave the EU.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","40148"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524214","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-14","<p>The Government is carefully considering the responses received to the discussion paper on options to support English regional airports from the potential impacts of air passenger duty devolution and will respond in due course.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-06-14T09:11:57.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524214/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524214/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524214/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-09","Air Passenger Duty","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he plans to publish the Government's response to the discussion paper on options for supporting English regional airports from the potential impacts of air passenger duty devolution, published in July 2015.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","40093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524215","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-17","<p>Estimates at England level of the numbers and proportions of homes ‘not meeting the decent homes standard’ by tenure are available from the English Housing Survey, 2014/15 Headline Report, Housing Stock, Annex Table 2.2 at the following link <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/english-housing-survey-2014-to-2015-headline-report" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/english-housing-survey-2014-to-2015-headline-report</a> Figures for years prior to 2006 are summarised in Live Table 119 at this link <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-dwelling-stock-including-vacants" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-dwelling-stock-including-vacants</a></p><p>Some information at local authority level is available from 2010 from various data returns from local authorities and private registered providers (housing associations) as follows:</p><p>Local authority housing data<br><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/local-authority-housing-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/local-authority-housing-data</a></p><p>Local Authority Business Plan Statistical Annex<br><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/business-plan-statistical-appendix-bpsa-data-returns-for-2010-11" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/business-plan-statistical-appendix-bpsa-data-returns-for-2010-11</a></p><p>Private Registered Providers:<br>Homes and Community Agency (HCA), Statistical Data Return<br><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistical-data-return-statistical-releases" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistical-data-return-statistical-releases</a></p><p>HCA Regulatory and Statistical Return<br>http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20120419011320/http:/www.tenantservicesauthority.org/server/show/nav.15039</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-06-17T15:21:22.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524215/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524215/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524215/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-06-09","Social Rented Housing: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many and what proportion of (a) local authority and (b) housing association homes in each English local authority area have not met the decent homes standard in each year since 2001.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","40126"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524216","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-16","<p>Officials in the Cities and Local Growth Unit will continue to work with the Tees Valley to implement their current devolution deal – including additional resources of £15 million per year, and over £100 million in already agreed growth deals. Tees Valley Combined Authority is already putting in place plans for implementing Lord Heseltine’s report. Government is committed to work coherently with local leaders to support the economic growth opportunities that have been identified.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-06-16T17:32:15.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524216/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524216/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524216/answer","Stockton South","James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524216/answer/previousversion/3853","Biography information for James Wharton","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-06-09","Local Growth Deals: Tees Valley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will provide additional resources to the Tees Valley Combined Authority and Local Enterprise Partnership to assist them in the key role envisioned for them in the independent report, Tees Valley: opportunity unlimited, published on 7 June 2016.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","40129"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524217","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-14","<p>The Department for Communities and Local Government does not hold information on the numbers of planning applications made in the Green Belt.</p><p>The department’s Land Use Change Statistics estimate that 3% of new residential addresses created in 2014-15 were in the Green Belt; unchanged from 2013-14. This equates to an estimated 3,900 homes – 2.9998% of the total homes built in the Green Belt in 2013-14, and 4,600 homes – 2.9997% of the total homes built in 2014-15.</p><p>The figures in the 13/14 publication are the first in the new series and so are not directly comparable to the previous Land Use Change Statistics which last published data covering the year 2011. Figures for 2011 and prior are available from the department’s website.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/land-use-change-statistics-in-england-2011" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/land-use-change-statistics-in-england-2011</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","40156","2016-06-14T17:04:11.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524217/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524217/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524217/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-06-09","Green Belt","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many applications were made by developers for housebuilding on green belt land in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","40163"
