"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524241","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-06-20","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer given by my rt. hon Friend the Secretary of State to the Hon. Member for Greenwich and Woolwich on 19 November 2015, Official Report Column 813-814:</p><p><a href="http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201516/cmhansrd/cm151119/debtext/151119-0001.htm" target="_blank">http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201516/cmhansrd/cm151119/debtext/151119-0001.htm</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-06-20T11:59:59.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524241/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524241/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524241/answer","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524241/answer/previousversion/3901","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-09","District Heating","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what plans she has to extend consumer protections to customers of district heating schemes.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","40167"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524242","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-06-27","<p>The Government has already set out long term visibility and certainty for the offshore wind industry in the UK, which is the largest market in the world.</p><p> </p><p>In November last year, my rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State announced that the UK could support up to 10GW of new offshore wind in the 2020s subject to costs continuing to fall. In Budget 2016 the Government announced that it will auction Contracts for Difference of up to £730 million this Parliament for up to 4GW of offshore wind and other less established renewables, with a first auction of £290 million. Support for offshore wind will be capped initially at £105/MWh (in 2011-12 prices), falling to £85/MWh for projects commissioning by 2026.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-06-27T09:06:49.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524242/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524242/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524242/answer","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524242/answer/previousversion/3900","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-09","Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, whether she plans to respond to the letter of 3 June 2016, from offshore wind companies to EU energy ministers in the June EU Energy Council.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","40104"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524243","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-06-14","<p>The Bonfield Review is an independent review, being led by Peter Bonfield. We expect the review to be published in the near future and will announce the date in due course.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-06-14T14:35:01.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524243/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524243/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524243/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-09","Consumer Advice, Protection, Standards and Enforcement for Energy Efficiency and Renewable Energy Independent Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, when she expects the Bonfield Review of consumer advice, protection standards and enforcement for energy efficiency and renewable energy to be published.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","40173"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524244","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-06-14","<p>The estimated evidence spend for core Defra for 2016/17 is £50m, of which £31m is planned to be spent in research and development (R&amp;D). The estimates for each of the remaining years of the Spending Review 2015 (SR15) period will not be finalised until the annual business planning round is concluded before the new financial year begins.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-06-14T16:54:42.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524244/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524244/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524244/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-06-09","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 9 June 2016 to Question 38502, what estimate she has made of her Department's (a) core total evidence spend and (b) core research and development spend in each of the next five years; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","40177"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524245","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-06-17","<p>The red squirrel is one of the UK’s most threatened native mammals, predominantly due to the threat posed by non-native grey squirrels, which out-compete red squirrels and spread the squirrel pox virus which is deadly to reds.</p><p> </p><p>It is a priority for Natural England to prevent the release of any such non-native species that might have a negative impact on our native fauna and flora.</p><p> </p><p>Natural England’s policy, therefore, is to not issue licences to release grey squirrels in counties or areas where red squirrels are, or may be, still present. Outside of those areas, licences are currently only issued for the re-release (within 1km of their point of capture) of rehabilitated animals that were originally taken from the wild for tending or treatment, or for immediate release of individuals at the same location from physical entrapment.</p><p> </p><p>A list of species of Union concern, identified under the EU Invasive Alien Species Regulation 1143/2014, will be coming into force later this year and will impose restrictions on the keeping, breeding, sale, transporting and release of 37 listed plants and animals, including the grey squirrel. Once this happens there may be a need to consider changes to the way Natural England licenses the keeping and release of these species. As a consequence Natural England is limiting grey squirrel licences to one year only.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-06-17T13:01:23.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524245/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524245/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524245/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-06-09","Squirrels: Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assurances she has received from Natural England that the system of wildlife licences provides adequate protection for red squirrel species.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","40113"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524246","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-06-15","<p>EU restrictions on the use of neonicotinoids have been fully implemented in the UK. Member States can authorise limited and controlled use of a pesticide on an exceptional basis in emergency situations to “control a danger which cannot be contained by any other reasonable means”. Emergency authorisations are not granted automatically and applications must be based on evidence relating to the need for the pesticide and possible harmful effects.</p><p> </p><p>Decisions on whether or not to grant authorisations for restricted neonicotinoids will be made on the basis of an examination of the technical and scientific information submitted by the applicant, by the UK Expert Committee on Pesticides and the Health and Safety Executive. Two applications are currently under consideration and will be assessed using the above regulatory criteria.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-06-15T09:54:43.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524246/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524246/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524246/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-06-09","Bees: Pesticides","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 4 May 2016 to Question 35884, on Bees: Pesticides, if she will make it her policy to exercise her powers to lift the temporary ban on neonicotinoids in the future; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","40149"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524247","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-13","<p>During the financial year 2015/16 the administrative cost of operating HMG’s network in Turkey was £8,598,421. For the financial year 2014/15 it was £11,085,874. For 2013/14 it was £9,402,577. For 2012/13 it was £8,462,061 and for 2011/12 it was £7,585,285.56. This includes the costs of all our missions in Turkey: the British Embassy in Ankara, the British Consulate General in Istanbul, the British Consulate in Izmir, the British Vice Consulate in Antalya, and the British Honorary Consulates in Bodrum, Fetiye and Marmaris. It does not include the cost of UK-based staff working in Turkey, which could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-07-13T16:02:19.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524247/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524247/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524247/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-09","Turkey: Diplomatic Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the cost was of operating the British Embassy in Ankara and the Consulate-General in Istanbul in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","40144"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524248","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-15","<p>The UK supports the Saudi Arabian-led Coalition military intervention in Yemen, which came at the request of legitimate President Hadi to deter aggression by the Houthis and forces loyal to the former president Saleh. Saudi Arabia and the Coalition have played a crucial role and the priority now is for the Yemeni parties to agree a political solution through UN-facilitated peace talks to end the conflict. The UK is not a member of the Saudi Arabian-led Coalition and UK’s arms exports to Saudi Arabia are made under pre-existing and long-standing government to government arrangements. The UK Government takes its arms export responsibilities very seriously and operates one of the most robust arms export control regimes in the world. The Government is satisfied that extant licences for Saudi Arabia are compliant with the UK’s export licensing criteria.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-06-15T14:42:26.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524248/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524248/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524248/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-09","Saudi Arabia: Arms Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the effect on the civil war in Yemen of arms sold by the UK to Saudi Arabia.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","40150"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524249","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-16","<p>We have made no such assessment.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-06-16T13:29:04.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524249/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524249/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524249/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-09","Israel: Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with reference to the Answers of 27 April 2016 to Questions 34797 and 34798, what assessment he has made of the implications for the UK's role in Israeli-Palestinian peace negotiations of UK funding being used by UN-funded non-governmental organisations to commemorate Palestinian terrorists.","false","Biography information for Bob Blackman","Harrow East","Bob Blackman","40140"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524250","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-13","<p>Four members of staff at the British Embassy in Ankara work either for all or part of their time on projects to promote reform and democratisation, as a full part of our work to promote UK interests in Turkey. The total annual cost of these staff for that project work was approximately £76,000 for Financial Year 2015/2016. This does not include the cost of the one UK-based member of staff which could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p>The UK remains committed to supporting security and prosperity across Europe, where we will continue to have close relationships and mutual interests.</p><p>In countries aspiring to join the EU, our bilateral focus will remain on strengthening stability, security, good governance and the economic fundamentals; and on building the resilience and capability to tackle global threats and challenges such as irregular migration and terrorism.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-07-13T15:58:32.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524250/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524250/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524250/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-09","Turkey: Diplomatic Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many people are part of the team working on projects to improve Turkey's prospects of joining the EU based at the British Embassy in Ankara; and what the total cost of that team was in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","40141"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524251","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-13","Staff in the projects team at the British Embassy in Ankara regularly meet their Turkish Government counterparts on a range of business, including promoting reform and democratisation towards European standards. The UK remains committed to supporting security and prosperity across Europe, where we will continue to have close relationships and mutual interests. In countries aspiring to join the EU, our bilateral focus will remain on strengthening stability, security, good governance and the economic fundamentals; and on building the resilience and capability to tackle global threats and challenges such as irregular migration and terrorism.","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-07-13T16:00:45.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524251/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524251/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524251/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-09","Turkey: Diplomatic Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many meetings the team working on projects to improve Turkey's prospects of joining the EU, based at the British Embassy in Ankara, have had with representatives of the Turkish government in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","40142"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524252","Department of Health","false","2016-06-16","<p>As part of the work to develop NHS England’s strategic framework for specialised services, NHS England and the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence will be working together closely to improve the adoption of highly specialised technologies. Further detail will be set out in the coming months in light of the conclusions of the Accelerated Access Review.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-06-16T09:17:02.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524252/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524252/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524252/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-09","Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to NHS England's consultation on a proposed method to support investment decisions in specialised commissioning, launched on 12 April 2016, if NHS England will issue a consultation on arrangements for commissioning treatments recommended through NICE's highly specialised technology programme.","false","Biography information for Crispin Blunt","Reigate","Crispin Blunt","40102"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524253","Department of Health","false","2016-06-16","<p>As yet, the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) does not have any plans to consult on changes to its methods and processes to support NHS England’s specialised commissioning process, but will carry out a full consultation if any such changes are considered necessary.</p><p> </p><p>Following NHS England’s review of its specialised commissioning processes and the publication in the summer of the final report from the Accelerated Access Review, we anticipate NICE will want to look at its processes and methods for the assessment of drugs and treatments used in specialised commissioning.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-06-16T09:15:14.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524253/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524253/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524253/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-09","Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans NICE has to consult on its methodology for carrying out evidence reviews and impact analyses to support NHS England's specialised commissioning process.","false","Biography information for Crispin Blunt","Reigate","Crispin Blunt","40103"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524254","Department of Health","false","2016-06-14","<p>We cannot be sure from our records how many times the list of medical conditions which provide eligibility for a medical exemption certificate has been reviewed since its introduction in 1968.</p><p> </p><p>The most recent external review commenced in 2008 when the then Prime Minister announced the addition of cancer to the list of conditions which would be eligible for a medical exception certificate, and announced at the same time that there would be a review by Professor Sir Ian Gilmore on how to implement exemptions for all those with long term conditions. The report of the Gilmore review was published in May 2010, and it was announced in the 2010 spending review that the recommendations made in the report would not be implemented in light of the financial situation. There are no current plans to undertake a further review of the list.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","40107","2016-06-14T14:02:23.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524254/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524254/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524254/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-09","Prescriptions: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many times the list of conditions eligible for a medical exemption certificate has been reviewed since its introduction.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","40106"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524255","Department of Health","false","2016-06-14","<p>We cannot be sure from our records how many times the list of medical conditions which provide eligibility for a medical exemption certificate has been reviewed since its introduction in 1968.</p><p> </p><p>The most recent external review commenced in 2008 when the then Prime Minister announced the addition of cancer to the list of conditions which would be eligible for a medical exception certificate, and announced at the same time that there would be a review by Professor Sir Ian Gilmore on how to implement exemptions for all those with long term conditions. The report of the Gilmore review was published in May 2010, and it was announced in the 2010 spending review that the recommendations made in the report would not be implemented in light of the financial situation. There are no current plans to undertake a further review of the list.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","40106","2016-06-14T14:02:23.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524255/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524255/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524255/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-09","Prescriptions: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether his Department plans to review the list of medical conditions eligible for a medical exemption certificate.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","40107"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524256","Department of Health","false","2016-06-14","<p>Following a recent review of the rate of NHS-funded Nursing Care (NHS FNC) in England, the Department has not yet announced the standard and higher rates of NHS FNC for 2016-17. We will make an announcement in due course.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-06-14T14:00:45.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524256/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524256/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524256/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-09","Nurses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the (a) standard and (b) higher rate for NHS-funded nursing care is for 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Heidi Alexander","Lewisham East","Heidi Alexander","40116"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524257","Department of Health","false","2016-06-14","<p>We are advised by NHS England that allocated funding for mental health services in the Haringey Clinical Commissioning Group area, which includes the Tottenham constituency, is £34.192 million, of which £31.326 million is allocated to Barnet, Enfield and Haringey Mental Health Trust.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-06-14T12:06:51.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524257/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524257/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524257/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-09","Mental Health Services: Tottenham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the mental health services budget is for people living in Tottenham.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","40121"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524258","Department of Health","false","2016-06-14","<p>We are advised by NHS England that the approach to suicide prevention in the London Borough of Haringey, which includes the Tottenham constituency, encompasses a range of wider public mental health initiatives, some of which are targeting specific population groups that are known to be at higher risk of mental ill health and suicide.</p><p> </p><p>We are further advised that a multi-agency plan is being developed by the local Suicide Prevention Alliance led by the voluntary sector and supported by Haringey Council and Haringey Clinical Commissioning Group.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-06-14T15:43:57.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524258/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524258/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524258/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-09","Mental Health Services: Tottenham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what progress has been made in implementing recommendation three of the Five Year Forward View for Mental Health, published in February 2016, on local multi-agency suicide prevention plans in Tottenham constituency.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","40122"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524259","Department of Health","false","2016-06-16","<p>The Department has no plans to issue any such directions to the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE).</p><p> </p><p>NHS England and clinical commissioning groups are legally required to fund drugs and treatments recommended in technology appraisal and highly specialised technologies guidance issued by the NICE, normally within three months of the publication of the NICE’s guidance.</p><p> </p><p>Following NHS England’s review of its specialised commissioning processes and the publication in the summer of the final report from the Accelerated Access Review, we anticipate the NICE will want to look at its processes and methods for the assessment of drugs and treatments used in specialised commissioning.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-06-16T09:18:18.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524259/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524259/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524259/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-09","Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to paragraph 10 of NHS England's Strategic Framework for Specialised Services board paper, published in May 2016, what plans his Department has to issue directions to NICE regarding the adoption of its guidance by NHS England for treatments recommended through (a) the technology appraisal programme and (b) the highly specialised treatment evaluation programme.","false","Biography information for Crispin Blunt","Reigate","Crispin Blunt","40123"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524260","Department of Health","false","2016-06-14","<p>As set out in the NHS England Board Paper, improving the adoption of new technologies and treatments will be an important element of NHS England’s strategic framework for specialised services. As part of the work to develop that framework, NHS England will be working with a range of stakeholders to explore how alternative reimbursement models could be deployed, including in the context of the recommendations of the Accelerated Access Review due for publication this summer.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-06-14T15:57:28.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524260/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524260/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524260/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-09","Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to paragraph 10 of NHS England's Strategic Framework for Specialised Services board paper, published in May 2016, what plans NHS England has to trial alternative reimbursement models for drugs and devices.","false","Biography information for Crispin Blunt","Reigate","Crispin Blunt","40124"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524261","Department of Health","false","2016-06-14","<p>Patient safety continues to be paramount and the rules include a ‘break glass’ provision for trusts should there be a need to pay in excess of the agency price caps for patient safety reasons. Trust boards are responsible for monitoring the impact of price caps and ensuring patient safety. More broadly, the Care Quality Commission Chief Inspector of Hospitals has been clear that he wants to see fewer agency staff because of the patient safety implications - continuity of care being so important to good services for patients.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-06-14T15:45:04.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524261/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524261/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524261/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-09","NHS: Temporary Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect of the capping of payments to NHS agency staff on levels of patient safety.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","40143"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524262","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-20","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-06-20T12:29:09.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524262/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524262/answer","UKSA response to 40133.pdf","UKSA response to 40133.pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - Clinical Commissioning","UKSA Letter to Member - Clinical Commissioning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524262/answer","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524262/answer/previousversion/3897","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-09","Clinical Commissioning Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many people are resident in the areas covered by each clinical commissioning group in England; and how many births were recorded in each such area in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Robert Flello","Stoke-on-Trent South","Robert Flello","40133"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524263","Department of Health","false","2016-06-14","<p>We have been developing our proposals for community pharmacy in 2016/17 and beyond in discussion with the Pharmaceutical Services Negotiating Committee (PSNC) and other stakeholders. We welcomed the publication of the PSNC’s counter proposal which is being considered as part of the consultation process. Our aim is to communicate our final decisions early in July.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","40162","2016-06-14T14:03:54.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524263/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524263/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524263/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-09","Pharmacy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what resources his Department has allocated to assessing the counter-proposal to the Government's plans for community pharmacy published by the Pharmaceutical Services Negotiating Committee in April 2016.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","40161"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524264","Department of Health","false","2016-06-14","<p>We have been developing our proposals for community pharmacy in 2016/17 and beyond in discussion with the Pharmaceutical Services Negotiating Committee (PSNC) and other stakeholders. We welcomed the publication of the PSNC’s counter proposal which is being considered as part of the consultation process. Our aim is to communicate our final decisions early in July.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","40161","2016-06-14T14:03:54.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524264/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524264/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524264/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-09","Pharmacy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether his Department plans to respond to the counter-proposal to the Government's plans for community pharmacy published by the Pharmaceutical Services Negotiating Committee in April 2016.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","40162"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524265","Department of Health","false","2016-06-14","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) is currently appraising nivolumab (Opdivo) for non-squamous non-small cell lung cancer.</p><p> </p><p>As part of its appraisal, the NICE has considered a patient access scheme (PAS) proposal from the manufacturer Bristol-Myers Squibb which has been agreed by Ministers. Departmental officials are open to discussing any further proposals regarding the PAS with the company.</p><p> </p><p>The NICE currently expects to publish its final guidance in September 2016.</p><p> </p><p>In the absence of the NICE guidance, it is for commissioners to make funding decisions based on the available evidence.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-06-14T15:59:28.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524265/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524265/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524265/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-09","Nivolumab","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will instruct officials of his Department to continue to work with the manufacturers of Nivolumab on ensuring that patients with non-squamous non-small cell lung cancer can access that drug through the NHS.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","40151"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524266","Department of Health","false","2016-06-14","<p>The information requested is not held centrally by the Department.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-06-14T11:52:15.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524266/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524266/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524266/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-09","NHS: Temporary Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the number of hospital shifts that have not been filled as a result of the introduction of caps to the number of NHS agency staff since (a) November 2015, (b) February 2016 and (c) April 2016.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","40190"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524267","Department of Health","false","2016-06-14","<p>The information requested is not held centrally by the Department. The latest NHS Workforce statistics (February 2016) are available on the Health and Social Care Information Centre website at:</p><p> </p><p>http://www.hscic.gov.uk/searchcatalogue?productid=20878&amp;topics=1%2fWorkforce%2fStaff+numbers&amp;sort=Relevance&amp;size=10&amp;page=1#top</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-06-14T13:37:23.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524267/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524267/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524267/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-09","NHS: Temporary Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the number of staff who have returned to permanent NHS jobs as a result of the introduction of caps on the number of NHS agency staff.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","40191"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524268","Department of Health","false","2016-06-14","<p>In December 2015, the NHS England Board published Allocation of resources to NHS England and the commissioning sector for 2016/17 to 2020/21, which set firm allocations for the years 2016/17 to 2018/19 and indicative allocations, to assist with planning, for the years 2019/20 and 2020/21.</p><p> </p><p>Part B of that paper is entitled Distribution of funds within each commissioning stream and paragraphs 34 to 38 describe the primary care allocation formula that was used to calculate the published allocations. Further details on the formula, including recent revisions and improvements to it, are outlined in annex E.</p><p> </p><p>Allocation of resources to NHS England and the commissioning sector for 2016/17 to 2020/21 is on the NHS England website at:</p><p>https://www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/04.PB_.17.12.15-Allocations.pdf</p><p> </p><p>In January 2016, the detailed NHS England Allocations Primary Care (medical) figures for 2016/17 to 2020/21 were published for clinical commissioning group (CCG) areas. These show firm allocations for 2016/17 to 2018/19 and indicative allocations, to help with planning, for 2019/20 and 2020/21. The paper is available on the NHS England website at:</p><p>https://www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/pc-medical-allocations.pdf</p><p> </p><p>In addition, the 44 Sustainability and Transformation Plan (STP) areas have received indicative allocations, which include: CCG expenditure on general practice, which is funded from CCG allocations; shares of general practice access funding; and also the mental health allocation, which will fund the additional therapists mentioned in the General Practice Forward View.</p><p> </p><p>Together the above account for around £2.1 billion of the £2.4 billion increase.</p><p> </p><p>There are a number of elements not included in the commissioning or STP allocations, including the Estates and Technology Transformation Fund (formerly the Primary Care Transformation Fund), capital funding and funding for general practitioner (GP) trainers and GP trainees. These other elements account for around £0.3 billion of the £2.4 billion increase, and it is yet to be determined how this funding will be allocated across the country.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-06-14T14:11:21.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524268/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524268/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524268/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-09","General Practitioners: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to NHS England's announcement, NHS England backs general practice with a multi-billion transformation plan, published on 21 April 2016, what formula his Department plans to use to determine the allocation of the £2.4 billion a year funding.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","40153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524269","Department of Health","false","2016-06-14","<p>Primary care, dental, optometry and pharmacy services are commissioned by NHS England on a London-wide basis, therefore there is no figure available for borough-level funding.</p><p> </p><p>Primary care medical (general practitioner (GP) services) allocations have been published for the next five years on a clinical commissioning group (CCG) -basis, the uplifts for Haringey are in the attached table.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The practice-level budgets for the GPs located within the Tottenham constituency total £18.4 million in 2016/17. These budgets are not set for future years but will be based on the practice-specific services and registered populations, as well as the national contract terms agreed in future years. They will benefit from the growth within the Haringey allocation as indicated in the table.</p><p> </p><p>There is a development under way for a new practice at Tottenham Hale for which the capital cost is £558,000 which will expand capacity within Tottenham. CCGs also commission additional medical services from GP practices from their own resources.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","40152","2016-06-14T12:05:36.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524269/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524269/answer","PQ40152 TABLE.xlsx","PQ40152 TABLE.xlsx","Practice-level budgets in Haringey","Practice-level budgets in Haringey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524269/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-09","General Practitioners: Haringey","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to NHS England's announcement, NHS England backs general practice with a multi-billion transformation plan, published on 21 April 2016, how much of the £2.4 billion a year funding will be allocated to GPs in (a) Tottenham constituency and (b) the London Borough of Haringey.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","40154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524270","Department of Health","false","2016-06-14","<p>Primary care, dental, optometry and pharmacy services are commissioned by NHS England on a London-wide basis, therefore there is no figure available for borough-level funding.</p><p> </p><p>Primary care medical (general practitioner (GP) services) allocations have been published for the next five years on a clinical commissioning group (CCG) -basis, the uplifts for Haringey are in the attached table.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The practice-level budgets for the GPs located within the Tottenham constituency total £18.4 million in 2016/17. These budgets are not set for future years but will be based on the practice-specific services and registered populations, as well as the national contract terms agreed in future years. They will benefit from the growth within the Haringey allocation as indicated in the table.</p><p> </p><p>There is a development under way for a new practice at Tottenham Hale for which the capital cost is £558,000 which will expand capacity within Tottenham. CCGs also commission additional medical services from GP practices from their own resources.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","40154","2016-06-14T12:05:36.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524270/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524270/answer","PQ40152 TABLE.xlsx","PQ40152 TABLE.xlsx","Practice-level budgets in Haringey","Practice-level budgets in Haringey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524270/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-09","Primary Health Care: Tottenham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the primary care budget is for people living in Tottenham constituency.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","40152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524271","Department of Health","false","2016-06-14","<p>The Department has no plans to introduce a new central data collection on the number of student nurses that have already studied for a degree before entering nurse training.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-06-14T14:53:34.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524271/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524271/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524271/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-09","Nurses: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 23 May 2016 to Question 37125, whether his Department has any plans to collect data on the number of student nurses that have already studied for a degree before entering nurse training.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","40189"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524272","Home Office","false","2016-06-24","<p>If an asylum seeker is granted refugee status written confirmation that there are no longer any restrictions on them living and working in the UK is posted to them. A Biometric Residence Permit and National Insurance number is also sent, which can then be used as evidence of their immigration status and in support of any application for benefits.</p><p>Statistics on the number of such cases are not recorded on centrally collated statistical databases and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost by examination of individual case records.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-06-24T14:08:16.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524272/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524272/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524272/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-06-09","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many asylum seekers who were granted refugee status were not provided with a (a) biometric residence permit and (b) National Insurance number by her Department before their 28-day asylum support ceased in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","40155"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524273","Home Office","false","2016-06-14","<p>The cost of obtaining any court transcript depends on the length of the proceedings.</p><p>The exact cost of the transcript in this case is unknown as no transcript has been requested to date by the Metropolitan Police Service.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-06-14T17:50:22.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524273/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524273/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524273/answer","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524273/answer/previousversion/3869","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-06-09","Gurpal Virdi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the cost to the Metropolitan Police is of obtaining a transcript of the Southwark Crown Court trial of charges against Gumpal Viladi.","false","Biography information for Sir Peter Bottomley","Worthing West","Sir Peter Bottomley","40178"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524274","Home Office","false","2016-06-14","<p>The Metropolitan Police Service has not provided this document to the Home Office.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-06-14T17:52:02.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524274/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524274/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524274/answer","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524274/answer/previousversion/3871","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-06-09","Metropolitan Police","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether the Metropolitan Police have provided her with a copy of the memorandum of a conviction/order entered in the Register of Lambeth East Juvenile Court that records the proving on 1 April 1987 of offences or complaints by PC Markwick by a defendant aged over 16 on 7 November 1986.","false","Biography information for Sir Peter Bottomley","Worthing West","Sir Peter Bottomley","40179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524275","Home Office","false","2016-06-15","<p>The Dublin Regulation is the mechanism for determining which EU Member State is responsible for examining an asylum claim, not whether an individual qualifies for asylum. Any request to the UK from another Member State to unite family members under the Dublin Regulation is carefully considered: where someone seeking asylum elsewhere in the EU can demonstrate they have close family members legally in the UK, we will take responsibility for that claim. We make decisions based on all evidence available to us and where it is coherent, verifiable and sufficiently detailed to establish family links.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-06-15T11:10:17.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524275/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524275/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524275/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-06-09","Asylum: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will provide additional funding for transfer cases related to the Dublin Regulation where further evidence of family links is needed for asylum to be granted.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","40147"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524276","Home Office","false","2016-06-15","<p>We support the principle of family unity and have several routes for families to be reunited safely. We do not hold collective figures on how many unaccompanied child refugees have been granted permission to join family in the UK; and what the countries of origin were of such children.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-06-15T11:10:33.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524276/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524276/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524276/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-06-09","Asylum: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, to how many unaccompanied child refugees her Department has granted permission to join family in the UK; and what the countries of origin were of such children.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","40127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524277","Home Office","false","2016-06-24","<p>As announced by the Prime Minister on 4 May and now reflected in the Immigration Act 2016, we will work to admit unaccompanied refugee children to the UK from elsewhere in the EU, where this is considered to be in the child's best interests.</p><p>As the legislation sets out, we need to consult with local authorities first and we are also working closely with NGOs, the UNHCR, UNICEF and relevant Member States to establish suitable processes to implement this initiative.</p><p>Ministers and senior officials are in ongoing discussions with Greece, Italy and France to identify and transfer to the UK unaccompanied refugee children where it is in their best interests. We are also consulting local authorities, non-governmental organisations and UNHCR. In addition, we have worked with France to improve the operation of the Dublin family reunification process, and accepted over 30 transfer requests between January and the end of April with many more cases in train.</p><p>We are committed to act as quickly as we can but we must take the necessary time to ensure we have the capacity to support those who are resettled. We must also ensure that we are able to continue to fulfil our obligations to children who are already in the UK.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-06-24T14:03:31.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524277/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524277/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524277/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-06-09","Asylum: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many unaccompanied child refugees have been reunited with relatives in the UK since the announcement, Unaccompanied asylum-seeking children to be resettled from Europe, on 4 May 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","40120"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524278","Home Office","false","2016-06-16","<p>The French NGO France Terre d’Asile (FTDA) has carried out a survey of children in the camps in the Calais area, which identified, within the scope of the survey, 43 children with claimed family links to the UK. We are working closely with the French Government and FTDA to ensure that where family links are established, transfers take place efficiently under the Dublin Regulation.</p><p>The transfer of cases deemed the responsibility of the UK on the basis of family unity provisions contained in the Dublin Regulation can take place relatively quickly and we have resources in place to facilitate this. An individual must first, however, claim asylum in France or another European state participating in the Regulation for the process to begin.</p><p>Under the UK-France Joint Declaration of 20 August 2015, the UK and France have committed to ensuring that the provisions of the Dublin III Regulation are used efficiently and effectively. To assist the handling of such cases, the two Governments have established a permanent official contact group, agreed single points of contact within respective Dublin Units and we seconded an asylum expert to the French administration to facilitate the improvement of all stages of the process.</p><p>The UK and France are running regular joint communication campaigns in northern France which inform unaccompanied children and others of their right to claim asylum in France and of the family reunion process.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","40098","2016-06-16T16:46:47.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524278/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524278/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524278/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524278/answer/previousversion/3873","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-06-09","Refugees: Calais","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many refugees currently housed in the refugee camp in Calais are unaccompanied children; and what steps are being taken to ensure that the asylum applications of those children are prioritised.","false","Biography information for Carol Monaghan","Glasgow North West","Carol Monaghan","40095"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524279","Home Office","false","2016-06-15","<p>We are currently carefully considering the report and its recommendations. The report acknowledges the progress made by the Home Office with regards to guidance and training provided to its staff but highlighted the Group’s view that there were some discrepancies between the Home Office policy and practice.</p><p>The Home Office carefully considers all asylum claims on their individual merits and grants protection for those who genuinely need it, in accordance with our international obligations under the Refugee Convention and the European Convention on Human Rights (ECHR). In every asylum case the particular circumstances of the individual are considered in light of published country information, which includes issues relating specifically to religious freedoms.</p><p>Published guidance on the interviewing and consideration of religious claims is regularly reviewed and takes into consideration the views of religious groups and other stakeholders.</p><p>All asylum decision makers are currently receiving credibility training. This course trains decision makers on how to assess the evidential value of their interview questions (including when assessing religious based claims and religious conversion), the various reasons why someone may not come across as credible in an asylum interview and discusses issues such as speculation and implausibility. The 5-week Foundation Training Programme (FTP) for new decision makers trains staff on all aspects of the asylum decision making process, including religious based claims and religious conversion has been endorsed by the UNHCR.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-06-15T11:09:55.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524279/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524279/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524279/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-06-09","Asylum: Religion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the implications for the Government's policy on asylum of the report by the All-Party Parliamentary Group for International Freedom of Religion or Belief, entitled Asylum report: inadequate assessment of religion-based claims, published in June 2016.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","40100"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524280","Home Office","false","2016-06-16","<p>The French NGO France Terre d’Asile (FTDA) has carried out a survey of children in the camps in the Calais area, which identified, within the scope of the survey, 43 children with claimed family links to the UK. We are working closely with the French Government and FTDA to ensure that where family links are established, transfers take place efficiently under the Dublin Regulation.</p><p>The transfer of cases deemed the responsibility of the UK on the basis of family unity provisions contained in the Dublin Regulation can take place relatively quickly and we have resources in place to facilitate this. An individual must first, however, claim asylum in France or another European state participating in the Regulation for the process to begin.</p><p>Under the UK-France Joint Declaration of 20 August 2015, the UK and France have committed to ensuring that the provisions of the Dublin III Regulation are used efficiently and effectively. To assist the handling of such cases, the two Governments have established a permanent official contact group, agreed single points of contact within respective Dublin Units and we seconded an asylum expert to the French administration to facilitate the improvement of all stages of the process.</p><p>The UK and France are running regular joint communication campaigns in northern France which inform unaccompanied children and others of their right to claim asylum in France and of the family reunion process.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","40095","2016-06-16T16:46:47.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524280/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524280/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524280/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524280/answer/previousversion/3874","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-06-09","Refugees: Calais","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many refugees currently housed in the refugee camp in Calais have immediate family members already resident in the UK; and what steps are being taken to reunite those families.","false","Biography information for Carol Monaghan","Glasgow North West","Carol Monaghan","40098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524281","Department for International Development","false","2016-06-16","<p>Providing a good quality education for all children, especially girls and those who are most disadvantaged is a priority for the Department. The UK supported 11 million children in school between 2010 and 2015. We have again committed to support 11 million children in the poorest countries gain a decent education by 2020. The UK has specifically committed to support 6.5 million girls in school by 2020. Our flagship Girls Education Challenge is ensuring that up to 1 million marginalised girls, progress through school with improved learning outcomes. In July DFID will be hosting a Girls’ Education Forum to drive the implementation of Global Goal 4 for girls and agree actions for making faster progress on girls’ education.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-06-16T09:30:07.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524281/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524281/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524281/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-06-09","Developing Countries: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that its support for education in its target countries reaches (a) girls and (b) other marginalised groups.","false","Biography information for Stephen Twigg","Liverpool, West Derby","Stephen Twigg","40172"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524282","Leader of the House","false","2016-06-15","<p>English is and should remain the language of this House. The Government has not made a detailed estimate of the cost of providing simultaneous and written translation in Welsh Grand Committees.</p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling",,"2016-06-15T15:29:23.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524282/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524282/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524282/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2016-06-09","Welsh Grand Committee: Translation Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, what estimate he has made of the potential cost of providing simultaneous and written translation in Welsh Grand Committees for bilingual proceedings.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","40145"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524283","Scotland Office","false","2016-06-14","<p>The UK Government provide funding to Citizens Advice Scotland (CAS), the umbrella organisation and membership body for the Citizens Advice Bureaux network in Scotland, through the Department for Business Innovation and Skills (BIS), and (via the Pension Wise service) through Her Majesty’s Treasury (HMT).</p><p> </p><p>The total UK Government funding to CAS over the past five financial years, including BIS and HMT funding, is set out below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total funding </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2015/16</strong></p></td><td><p>£9,583,511</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014/15</strong></p></td><td><p>£8,797,196</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013/14</strong></p></td><td><p>£5,614,800</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2012/13</strong></p></td><td><p>£6,887,500</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2011/12</strong></p></td><td><p>£2,900,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Funding increased substantially between 2011/12 and 2012/13 to reflect the additional functions CAS had taken on as a result of the consumer landscape changes, including the joint delivery (with Citizens Advice England and Wales) of the Consumer Service helpline, education and advocacy on general consumer issues, and as the advocate on behalf of consumers in the regulated energy and postal sectors.</p><p> </p><p>Funding also increased substantially between 2013/14 and 2014/15 when the Government established the Pension Wise service to offer free and impartial guidance to people on the new pension freedoms which came into effect in April 2015.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2016-06-14T14:37:50.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524283/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524283/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524283/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-06-09","Citizens Advice Scotland: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how much funding the Government provided to Citizens Advice Scotland in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","40187"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524284","Department for Transport","false","2016-06-14","<p>Network Rail is responsible for the national rail timetable and modelled the timetable changes associated with the redevelopment of London Bridge station. We do not have information on the cost of individual modelling exercises.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-06-14T11:02:46.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524284/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524284/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524284/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-06-09","Railways: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, which organisation (a) was responsible and (b) carried out the modelling on punctuality and reliability of the combined impact of the infrastructure restrictions at London Bridge, the diversion of Thameslink services and the increased use of London Victoria as a terminus; how much that modelling cost; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","40199"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524285","Department for Transport","false","2016-06-14","<p>There is a process in place with regard to the publication of documents and any redaction of information. Only once the redactions have been agreed by all parties, including the Department, can publication take place.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-06-14T11:06:16.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524285/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524285/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524285/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-06-09","Govia Thameslink Railway","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, for what reasons the redacted Govia Thameslink Railway remedial plan, dated 12 February 2016, was not made publicly available until 26 May 2016.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","40171"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524286","Department for Transport","false","2016-06-14","<p>There are 15.5 full time equivalent officials of the Department working on the invitation to tender for the West Midlands rail franchise. This count includes two full time secondments within the team but does not include advisers contracted to work on the invitation to tender.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-06-14T11:43:18.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524286/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524286/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524286/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-06-09","Railways: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many full-time equivalent officials of his Department are working on the invitation to tender for the West Midlands rail franchise; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","40164"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524287","Department for Transport","false","2016-06-14","<p>We will be responding to the Hendy Report later this year. In the meantime, we are working with Network Rail to identify how Access for All projects will be delivered and when. The decision about Access for All schemes will be made later this summer. These will be set out in updated versions of the Enhancement Delivery Plans currently available Network Rail’s website.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-06-14T10:26:23.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524287/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524287/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524287/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-06-09","Railway Stations: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when his Department plans to decide which stations will be affected by Network Rail's decision to defer Access to All works from Control Period 5 into Control Period 6; and how the outcome of that decision will be published.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","40118"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524288","Department for Transport","false","2016-06-14","<p>Over one hundred responses have been received to my Department’s consultation on the recommendations of Sir Peter Hendy’s report, a number of which reference Access for All works. My Department is committed to publishing a report summarising these responses and decisions made in light of them later this year.</p><p> </p><p>In addition to the consultation my Department has received letters from a wide range of stakeholders discussing a variety of Access for All subjects, a number of whom Ministers and officials have also met.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-06-14T12:17:54.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524288/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524288/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524288/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-06-09","Railway Stations: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what representations his Department has received on the recommendation of Sir Peter Hendy's report published in November 2015, on replanning of Network Rail's Investment Programme to defer Access to All works from Control Period 5 to Control Period 6.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","40119"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524289","Department for Transport","false","2016-06-27","<p>We are working with Network Rail to identify how Access for All projects will be delivered and we will be responding to the Hendy Report later this year. The majority of projects should still be delivered by 2019 or have a design completed so that they can start work on site as soon as available funding allows. Option selection and design work for the project at Lichfield Trent Valley is ongoing.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-06-27T12:43:07.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524289/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524289/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524289/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-06-09","Lichfield Trent Valley Station","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he expects work to commence on providing disabled access to all platforms at Lichfield Trent Valley railway station in response to his Department's review of the Access for all programme; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Michael Fabricant","Lichfield","Michael Fabricant","40101"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524290","Department for Transport","false","2016-06-15","<p>The Government has made clear its intention to make this country a cycling nation. The Cycling and Walking Investment Strategy will be published in the summer and will include details of how the £300m committed in the last Spending Review will be invested to support cycling and walking.</p><p> </p><p>In addition to the dedicated cycling and walking programmes, there are a number of wider funding streams which are devolved to local bodies and which can and are being used to support cycling and walking projects. In particular, billions are available to Local Enterprise Partnerships and local authorities through the Local Growth Fund and Integrated Transport Block allocations.</p><p> </p><p>In addition to the above, a record £6.1 billion has been allocated to local highways authorities between 2015 and 2021 for road maintenance, and this funding can help maintain footways and cycleways.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-06-15T16:23:08.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524290/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524290/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524290/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-06-09","Cycling and Walking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what additional funding his Department plans to make available for walking and cycling initiatives as a result of the cycling and walking investment strategy.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","40114"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524291","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-06-15","<p>For all Work Choice providers excluding Remploy, there have been 2,070 starts in Scotland in the financial year 2013/14, 1,780 in 2014/15, and 1,210 in 2015/16.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-06-15T12:12:42.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524291/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524291/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524291/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-06-09","Employment Schemes: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what information his Department holds on the number of starts in Scotland on the Work Choice programme in each of the last three financial years for which such information is available.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","40135"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524292","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-06-15","<p>My department has not undertaken any research on this topic.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-06-15T12:17:08.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524292/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524292/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524292/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-06-09","Personal Income","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what research his Department has undertaken on the potential merits of implementing a universal basic income.","false","Biography information for Ronnie Cowan","Inverclyde","Ronnie Cowan","40099"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524293","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-06-15","<p>For all Work Choice providers excluding Remploy, there have been 2,780 referrals in Scotland in the financial year 2013/14, 2,270 in 2014/15, and 1,510 in 2015/16.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-06-15T12:04:02.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524293/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524293/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524293/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-06-09","Employment Schemes: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what information his Department holds on the number of referrals for individuals in Scotland to the Work Choice programme in each of the last three financial years for which such information is available.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","40138"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524294","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-06-14","<p>Where CSA arrears are moved across to the CMS system we will actively pursue collection where the CSA clients fall within three specific scenarios. These include firstly where a re-application has been made to CMS relating to the same case; secondly where the CSA arrears were being paid in the last 3 months prior to being moved over to the CMS system; and finally where a client actively requests we collect them.</p><p> </p><p>Given this approach to the collection of these CSA arrears, they are collected through our business-as-usual processes within our Case Maintenance, Arrears and Enforcement Teams within CMS, where at June 2016 there were 3,256 full time equivalent staff.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-06-14T16:17:16.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524294/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524294/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524294/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-06-09","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 27 May 2016 to Question 37474, how many full-time equivalent officials of his Department are responsible for any debt collection activity that the CMS system is undertaking to ensure that former Child Support Agency child maintenance arrears are received.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","40130"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524295","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-06-14","<p>The impact assessment was completed in 2013, well before CSA cases started to be closed. These numbers have since been reviewed to reflect the experiences of the case closure journey. The initial estimate of £103m to review the cases has reduced to £75m as the updating work has taken less time than assumed when the impact assessment was completed. The initial estimate to set up the arrears on the CMS system was £20m and this is proving to take longer than anticipated, with the latest estimate at £26m. The revised figures are still subject to further change as we move more cases and update estimates.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-06-14T16:23:37.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524295/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524295/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524295/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-06-09","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 27 May 2016 to Question 37474, on children: maintenance, what specific areas of case closure require less effort than earlier analysis suggested.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","40131"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524296","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-06-14","<p>HSE estimate the total level of income from commercial sources will be £17m in 2016/17. Future year income estimates will be determined as part the business planning process and included as part of the published Business Plan.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-06-14T09:03:46.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524296/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524296/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524296/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-06-09","Health and Safety Executive","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will estimate the level of income that the Health and Safety Executive will receive from commercial sources in each year up to 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","40134"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524297","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-06-15","<p>For all Work Choice providers excluding Remploy, there have been 1,350 job outcomes in Scotland in the financial year 2013/14, 1,290 in 2014/15, and 700 in 2015/16.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-06-15T12:07:44.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524297/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524297/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524297/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-06-09","Employment Schemes: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what information his Department holds on the number of job outcomes in Scotland for the Work Choice programme in each of the last three financial years for which such information is available.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","40137"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524299","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-20","<p>The Government does not hold figures for the number of former military personnel from Saddam Hussein’s regime that joined Daesh. However, there are credible reports of several ex-Ba’athist senior military officials and personnel with weapons expertise having joined Daesh.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-06-20T12:41:33.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524299/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524299/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524299/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-09","Fire and Rescue Services: Staff","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of the number of Saddam Hussein’s elite guards and soldiers who have joined ISIS in Iraq and Syria.","false","Biography information for Lord Ahmed",,"Lord Ahmed","HL570"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524300","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-16","<p>We are supporting the Iraqi government in its efforts to unite Iraq’s communities against Daesh and extremism, rebuild public trust in the Iraqi state and deliver the services and opportunities which all Iraqis want and deserve. We welcome the commitments that the Government of Iraq has made to inclusivity, to protecting Iraqi citizens, to addressing human rights abuses and holding those responsible to account.</p><p> </p><p>There are now more than 3 million internally displaced people in Iraq. We have committed £79.5 million to the humanitarian effort in Iraq to help those who have fled Daesh’s brutality, and are the largest donor to the Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs-managed Iraq Humanitarian Pooled Fund.</p><p> </p><p>We are contributing £6 million to the UN’s Funding Facility for Immediate Stabilisation, to help the Iraqi government stabilise areas recently liberated from Daesh and re-establish security, basic services and inclusive local governance. We will provide funding for a number of projects designed to support community cohesion and encourage reconciliation, acceptance and tolerance between communities at a grass roots level.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-06-16T14:37:11.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524300/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524300/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524300/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-09","Prum Convention","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they plan to take to encourage Kurdish Iraqis, Sunnis and Shia Muslims to live together after defeating ISIS in Iraq.","false","Biography information for Lord Ahmed",,"Lord Ahmed","HL571"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524301","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-16","<p>The Government has not made an estimate of the number of Iraqis killed as a result of terrorism and war-related violence since 2003. While the security situation in Iraq has greatly improved since violence peaked in 2006-2007, Iraqi civilians have been victim to Daesh’s atrocities since the summer of 2014. We utterly condemn such violence and call for those responsible to be brought to justice. The UK is committed to supporting the Government of Iraq as it works to defeat Daesh and put Iraq on the path to long-term peace and stability.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-06-16T14:38:01.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524301/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524301/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524301/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-09","EU Justice and Home Affairs","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the total number of Iraqi civilians killed since the start of the 2003 Iraq war.","false","Biography information for Lord Ahmed",,"Lord Ahmed","HL572"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524302","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-16","<p>We are aware that the Iranian Revolutionary Guard Corps is on the ground in both advisory and combat roles in Iraq and that Iran is providing significant funding, training and equipment to elements of Iraq’s Popular Mobilisation Forces.</p><p> </p><p>Along with our international partners, the UK has consistently made clear that there is a role for all of Iraq’s neighbours in helping defeat Daesh. We have no difficulty with contributions from around the region to the goal of ridding Iraq of the Daesh threat, provided that those contributions are authorised by the Iraqi government. We will continue to work closely with our international partners to encourage all of Iraq’s neighbours to play a transparent and constructive role in its affairs.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-06-16T14:38:35.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524302/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524302/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524302/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-09","Georgia: Russia","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have gathered any evidence of Iranian fighters in Iraq.","false","Biography information for Lord Ahmed",,"Lord Ahmed","HL573"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524303","Department of Health","false","2016-06-14","<p>This is an operational matter for the Commissioning Support Unit and the local Council.</p><p> </p><p>The North of England Commissioning Support Unit advises that it has held discussions with the Director of Public Health but is not aware of any offer to place a contract with the organisation.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-06-14T13:15:06.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524303/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524303/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524303/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-09","Free Schools","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government why the North East Commissioning Service has not accepted an offer from Newcastle City Council's Director of Public Health to place a contract to modify data systems to facilitate analysis at council ward level.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL574"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524304","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-21","<p>The Electoral Commission will publish the total electorate for the EU referendum in due course.</p>",,"Baroness Evans of Bowes Park",,"2016-06-21T16:04:34.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524304/answer","Biography information for Baroness Evans of Bowes Park","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524304/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524304/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-09","Social Security Benefits: Asylum","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the fact that four million people have been added to the electoral register in recent months, whether they will publish details of the comparison between the final register for the EU referendum and that as at December 2015, and if so when.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL575"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524305","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-16","<p>Criminal proceedings connected to the subject matter of the Leveson Inquiry, including the appeals process, have not yet been completed. We‎ have always been clear that these cases must conclude before we consider Part 2 of the Inquiry.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-06-16T12:07:29.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524305/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524305/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524305/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-06-09","Training","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answer by Baroness Neville-Rolfe on 26 January (HL Deb, col 1152), whether it is their policy that the trial of Mazher Mahmood would need to be completed before Part 2 of the Leveson Inquiry could take place.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hollins",,"Baroness Hollins","HL576"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524306","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-22","<p>I refer the noble Lord to the answer given by my hon. Friend the Minister of State for Defence Procurement (Mr Philip Dunne) in the House of Commons on 8 February 2016, to Question number 25165. Type 45 destroyers were designed for world-wide operations, from sub-Arctic to extreme tropical environments and continue to operate effectively in the Persian Gulf and South Atlantic at all times of the year.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-06-22T11:16:33.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524306/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524306/answer","Hansard Extract 8 February 2016  HOC 25165.docx","Hansard Extract 8 February 2016  HOC 25165.docx","Type 45 Destroyers: Repair and Maintenance","Type 45 Destroyers: Repair and Maintenance","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524306/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-09","Stop and Search: Ethnic Groups","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what action they are taking to remedy the problems caused by the failure in hot climates of intercooler units on Type 45 destroyers.","false","Biography information for Lord Hoyle",,"Lord Hoyle","HL577"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524307","Home Office","false","2016-06-16","<p>The Government has no legal basis to influence where UK citizens choose to live.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-06-16T14:50:31.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524307/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524307/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524307/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-06-09","Police: Ethnic Groups","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to tackle the decline in the number of UK citizens moving to live overseas.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones of Cheltenham",,"Lord Jones of Cheltenham","HL578"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524308","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-15","<p>Regional trade statistics at the local authority level are not available.</p><p> </p><p>Trade statistics showing the value of trade in goods between UK regions/countries (NUTS 1 level) and EU member states are available from the HM Revenue and Customs’ Regional Trade Statistics database.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Price",,"2016-06-15T12:25:04.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524308/answer","Biography information for Lord Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524308/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524308/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-09","NHS: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of the value of (1) imports, and (2) exports, from other EU member states to each local authority area in the UK.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kramer",,"Baroness Kramer","HL579"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524309","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-15","<p>Companies House’s role is to hold the register of UK companies and make the information available to the public. Its role is not to provide detailed analysis on companies. Providing an accurate figure on the number and value of UK companies that are subsidiaries of other non-UK companies would breach the disproportionate cost threshold given the volume and complexity of the information within the dataset.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-06-15T15:10:22.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524309/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524309/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524309/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-09","Cancer: Young People","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many UK companies are subsidiaries of another company that is registered (1) within the EU, or (2) in the rest of the world; and what estimate they have made of the total value of those UK companies.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kramer",,"Baroness Kramer","HL580"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524310","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-23","<p>Whilst private landlords are competing for properties in the same housing market as owner occupiers, the types and locations of properties that they prefer will not always be identical to owner occupiers. Recent research by the Bank of England – see <a href="https://bankunderground.co.uk/2015/07/21/five-facts-about-buy-to-let/" target="_blank">https://bankunderground.co.uk/2015/07/21/five-facts-about-buy-to-let/</a> - shows that buy to let investors have a greater tendency to purchase apartments and properties in London than owner occupiers.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-06-23T14:19:52.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524310/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524310/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524310/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-06-09","Serco","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what evidence they have collected that buy-to-let investors and prospective residential owner-occupiers are in competition in the market for the same properties.","false","Biography information for The Earl of Lytton",,"The Earl of Lytton","HL581"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524311","Department for Transport","false","2016-06-14","<p>The Government has no current plans to amend the non-statutory guidance to local authorities about the Blue Badge scheme. As the guidance makes clear “Each application should be considered on its merits – not on a “one size fits all” basis. The final decision about whether an applicant meets the criterion is for the issuing authority to make.”.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-06-14T10:57:53.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524311/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524311/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524311/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-06-09","GEOAmey PECS","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to amend Section 4:4 of <i>The Blue Badge Scheme Local Authority Guidance </i>(<i>England</i>) to exclude the first sentence that specifies certain medical conditions in order to ensure that eligibility is based on disability or ill health regardless of diagnosis.","false","Biography information for The Countess of Mar",,"The Countess of Mar","HL582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524312","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-06-16","<p>We are developing a digital service for claiming Personal Independence Payment (PIP) which brings the current PIP telephony claim and paper form together.</p><p>We have tested a number of different design approaches with users and, based on feedback, are developing an application process that is more tailored to individual needs. From April 2016 we started making the online PIP claim available to a small number of PIP claimants on a voluntary basis. This will allow us to get direct feedback, make ongoing improvements and ensure this new service is effective and secure before it is available nationally.</p>",,"Baroness Altmann",,"2016-06-16T14:20:46.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524312/answer","Biography information for Baroness Altmann","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524312/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524312/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-06-09","Young Offenders: Restraint Techniques","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether there is any provision for people claiming Personal Independence Payments who have difficulty in completing questions by hand to be able to complete the forms electronically; and if not, whether they plan to introduce such a facility.","false","Biography information for The Countess of Mar",,"The Countess of Mar","HL583"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524313","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-23","<p>In 2010 there were 20.3 million visits to the UK from the EU, and 24.2 million in 2015. This data is not available for 2000. This Government is committed to further increasing the number of visitors to the UK and growing the tourism industry across the whole of Britain, as set out in our Five Point Plan, which can be found on the attached report.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-06-23T15:34:27.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524313/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524313/answer","Tourism_-_A_Five_Point_Plan.pdf","Tourism_-_A_Five_Point_Plan.pdf","Backing the Tourism Sector - a five point plan","Backing the Tourism Sector - a five point plan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524313/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-06-09","Pregnancy: Restraint Techniques","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many visitors from the EU came to the UK in (1) 2000, (2) 2010, and (3) 2015.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL584"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524314","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-23","<p>In 2011, tourists from the EU spent £8.26 billion in the UK. This was £8.28 billion in 2012, £9.19 billion in 2013, £9.55 billion in 2014 and £9.71 billion in 2015. This Government is committed to further growing the tourism industry across the whole of Britain, encouraging more visitors to travel beyond the capital.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-06-23T15:36:07.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524314/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524314/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524314/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-06-09","Feltham Young Offender Institution","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the estimated income from tourists from the EU who visited the UK in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524315","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-23","<p>In 2011, 2.8 per cent of employment in all UK tourism industries came from the pre-accession EU 15 member states. An additional 3.9 per cent of employment in all UK tourism industries came from the newer EU states: Poland, Lithuania, Hungary, Bulgaria, Slovakia, Romania, Latvia, Czech Republic, Malta, Estonia, Cyprus, and Slovenia. This data is the most up to date that we hold.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-06-23T15:38:47.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524315/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524315/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524315/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-06-09","S4C: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many hospitality industry employees in the UK were from other EU member states in each of the last five years, and which countries they were from.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL586"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524316","Department of Health","false","2016-06-14","<p>The number of overseas citizens working in the United Kingdom in hospitals and care homes is not collected centrally.</p><p> </p><p>The Health and Social Care Information Centre (HSCIC) publishes data on the number of staff working in National Health Service hospital and community health services in England. The HSCIC also publishes data on the nationality of NHS staff, which is a self-reported field within the NHS human resources and payroll system, the electronic staff record (ESR). The nationality information entered by an individual employee onto ESR may reflect their cultural heritage rather than their country of birth.</p><p> </p><p>From the 1,151,138 headcount number of staff working in NHS trusts and clinical commissioning groups as at September 2015, 1,056,773 have self-declared their nationality. Of these, 217,063 (21%) have declared as having nationalities other than British.</p><p> </p><p>Skills for Care, the partner in the Sector Skills Council for social care, collects information on the nationality of the adult social care workforce in England.</p><p> </p><p>Skills for Care estimates that there were on average 135,000 residential care job roles filled by non-British adult social care workers in England in 2015.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-06-14T15:03:03.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524316/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524316/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524316/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-09","S4C: Public Appointments","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many overseas citizens work in the UK in (1) hospitals, and (2) care homes.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL587"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524317","Department of Health","false","2016-06-14","<p>The question has been interpreted to mean contributions to the Clinical Negligence Scheme for Trusts (CNST) which provides indemnity for National Health Service bodies. These are not insurance premiums.</p><p> </p><p>The total cost for 2014-15, which is the last available published figure, is £1,037,742,810.</p><p> </p><p>The information as to which NHS Foundation Trust pays the highest amount as a percentage of its budget is not held centrally.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-06-14T13:15:40.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524317/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524317/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524317/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-09","S4C","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the total cost to the NHS of insurance premiums for clinical negligence; which Foundation Trust pays the highest amount as a percentage of its budget; and what percentage of its budget that cost represents.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL588"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524318","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-15","<p>As an independent corporation North East Surrey College of Technology is responsible for ensuring appropriate safeguards and governance arrangements are in place in relation to the corporation including subsidiary companies. The Skills Funding Agency has received a report from NESCOT and is considering whether there is any risk to public funds and if so what action should be taken.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-06-15T15:11:03.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524318/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524318/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524318/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-09","S4C: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what safeguards and governance arrangements have been put in place to prevent a recurrence of the situation where (1) the Principal of North East Surrey College of Technology allegedly paid her husband over £170,000 during the course of a contract with a Saudi Arabian college, and (2) the Board of Governors were unaware for over 18 months that such payments were made.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL589"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524319","Department for Transport","false","2016-06-17","<p>As rickshaws (pedicabs) outside London are regulated as taxis (Hackney Carriages), it is down to each local authority to set the licensing conditions, standards and by-laws for both driver and vehicle. This includes ensuring the health and safety of all travelling passengers, for instance through policies on vehicle type and safety features.</p><p> </p><p>This function is the responsibility of the local licensing authority.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-06-17T10:29:57.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524319/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524319/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524319/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-06-09","Abortion","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 8 June (HL342), what regulations are in place to ensure the health and safety of paying passengers outside London; and who is responsible for that function.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL590"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524320","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-23","<p>Green belts are created and protected by local authorities in line with national policy set out in the National Planning Policy Framework (NPPF). A Green Belt boundary can only be altered where there are exceptional circumstances and only by means of the Local Plan process of public consultation and independent examination.</p><p>We do not define exceptional circumstances as these can vary from instance to instance. The NPPF however does outline that exceptions in regards to the construction of new buildings in the Green Belt may include:</p><ul><li>buildings for agriculture and forestry;</li><li>provision of appropriate facilities for outdoor sport and recreation and for cemeteries as long as it preserves the openness of the Green Belt and does not conflict with the purposes of including land within it;</li><li>the extension or alteration of a building provided that it does not result in disproportionate additions over and above the size of the original building;</li><li>limited infilling in villages, and limited affordable housing for local community needs under policies set out in the Local Plan.</li></ul>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-06-23T14:22:37.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524320/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524320/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524320/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-06-09","Social Rented Housing: Rents","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 7 June (HL272), what are the National Planning Policy Framework guidelines about what constitutes an exceptional circumstance that necessitates building on Green Belt land.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL591"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525192","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-16","<p>This Government the UK has taken a global lead on tackling the scourge of corruption. Each delegation signed up to the commitments set out in the communiqué. In addition, 42 countries and 8 international organisations issued statements setting out further measures they will take.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-06-16T14:47:43.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525192/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525192/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525192/answer","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525192/answer/previousversion/4131","Biography information for Matt Hancock","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-09","Anti-corruption Summit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment he has made of the potential effectiveness of the agreements reached at the Anti-Corruption Summit in May 2016 in tackling corruption.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","905422"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525193","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-16","<p>NCS is open to all young people and can significantly improve life chances. 7 in 10 participants felt more confident about getting a job in the future after NCS. Young people eligible for free school meals participate in high numbers and demonstrate stronger positive impacts in building resilience. The NCS Bill will make NCS a permanent feature of British life for young people from every background.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-06-16T15:00:46.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525193/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525193/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525193/answer","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525193/answer/previousversion/4137","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-09","Voluntary Work: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment he has made of the effect of the National Citizen Service on life chances.","false","Biography information for Huw Merriman","Bexhill and Battle","Huw Merriman","905420"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525194","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-15","<p>As set out in our manifesto for this parliament, the Government will bring forward proposals amending the Representation of the People Act 1985 to remove the outdated 15 year time limit on overseas voting rights. Subject to the necessary Parliamentary approval, we intend to have this fully in place for the next European Parliamentary elections and UK Parliamentary elections in 2019 and 2020, respectively.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2016-06-15T12:34:20.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525194/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525194/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525194/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-09","Electorate","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will bring forward legislative proposals to amend provisions of the Representation of the People Act 1983 relating to the franchise.","false","Biography information for Peter Grant","Glenrothes","Peter Grant","905417"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523832","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-13","<p>The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS) has carried an Equality Analysis to consider the impact of the decision on staff with protected characteristics, in compliance with the Public Sector Equality Duty.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-06-13T15:57:40.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523832/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523832/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523832/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-08","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Reorganisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Written Statement of 26 May 2016, HCWS30, whether his Department carried out an equality effect assessment on the effect on the public of the decision to centralise policy functions in his Department's London office.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","39894"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523833","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-14","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>My officials have been engaging employers throughout the policy development to gain their insight and advice. As part of the formal consultation last year, over 700 responses were received from employers. Opinions were evenly split as to whether levy funding should only be used to pay for the direct costs of apprenticeship training and assessment. Further information is available in the published Government response.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-06-14T12:52:19.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523833/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523833/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523833/answer","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523833/answer/previousversion/3444","Biography information for Nick Boles","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-08","Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, which bodies have made representations to the Government on the inclusion of administration costs, travel and wages in the funding for the Digital Apprenticeship System; and what proportion of bodies making such representations were in favour of the Government's proposals.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","39941"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523834","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-16","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>A provider’s performance in the three areas of Teaching Quality, Learning Environment, and Student Outcomes and Learning Gain will not be subject to individual ratings<em>.</em> Assessors will make a holistic assessment, considering all three areas, in order to award a single TEF rating for the provider.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-06-16T10:26:43.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523834/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523834/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523834/answer","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523834/answer/previousversion/3448","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-08","Higher Education: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether a provider would need to achieve an Excellent rating in (a) one, (b) two or (c) three of the Teaching Quality, Learning Environment and Student Outcomes and Learning Gain categories in order to achieve an overall Excellent rating under the Teaching Excellence framework.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","39919"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523836","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-14","<p>My Rt hon Friend the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills recently announced plans to expedite this Insolvency Service investigation. It is not appropriate for details of the ongoing investigation to be made public as that may prejudice the outcome of any criminal or civil cases which arise from it. This is long standing Insolvency Service policy. However, I have met with the Insolvency Service to discuss the conduct of the investigation and will expect to do so periodically as the investigation progresses.</p><p> </p><p>If any directors are disqualified the Insolvency Service will publish the details of the disqualification on its website (for three months) and will notify Companies House, which keeps the statutory register of disqualifications. In addition, where the investigation uncovers matters of potential criminal misconduct or other regulatory breaches then this will be reported to the relevant authority for further action.</p><p> </p><p>Once the investigation is completed the Government will consider what detail it is appropriate to publish having full regard to any legal restrictions and on the legitimate public interest in the cause of the BHS failure.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-06-14T13:28:49.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523836/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523836/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523836/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523836/answer/previousversion/3470","Biography information for Anna Soubry","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-08","British Home Stores: Insolvency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, by when he expects the findings from the Insolvency Service investigation into BHS to be published.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","39931"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523837","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-13","<p>The main aim of the Pye Tait research is to provide a qualitative and quantitative assessment of the costs and benefits of the contractual practice of holding retentions in construction.</p><p>My Department is currently working with Pye Tait to finalise this research. It will be published alongside a consultation document later this year.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-06-13T10:18:35.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523837/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523837/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523837/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-08","Construction: Industry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, in which month the Pye Tait Review of retentions in the construction industry will be published.","false","Biography information for Mr Mark Prisk","Hertford and Stortford","Mr Mark Prisk","39981"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523839","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-13","<p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>My Department has no direct responsibility for Building Regulations Part G as this falls to the Department for Communities and Local Government and is enforced through local authorities who have a general duty to enforce Building Regulations in their area.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-06-13T10:11:19.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523839/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523839/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523839/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-08","Building Regulations: Water","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what resources his Department has allocated to the Regulatory Delivery Directorate for enforcement of part G of the Building Regulations 2010 in domestic properties.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","40034"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523840","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-14","<p>Details of Ministers' meetings with external organisations are published on a quarterly basis. In line with the practice of previous administrations, details of internal meetings are not normally disclosed.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-06-14T08:55:03.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523840/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523840/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523840/answer","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523840/answer/previousversion/3376","Biography information for Matt Hancock","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-08","Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many meetings Ministers of his Department had to discuss tax evasion and avoidance between (a) 5 April 2016 and 5 May 2016 and (b) 6 May 2016 and 6 June 2016.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","39936"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523841","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-13","<p>In line with the practice of successive administrations, details of ministerial discussions are not normally disclosed.</p><p> </p><p>The government is committed to ensuring that everyone makes a fair contribution towards reducing the deficit. We have already announced, during this Parliament, that we will legislate for over 25 measures to tackle avoidance, evasion and aggressive tax planning, which are forecast to raise £16 billion by 2021.</p><p> </p><p>We also announced that HMRC would receive an extra £800 million, at Summer Budget 2015, to fund additional work to 2020-21. This will enable HMRC to recover a cumulative £7.2 billion in tax over the next five years by tackling evasion and non-compliance.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-06-13T14:02:51.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523841/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523841/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523841/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-08","Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many meetings Ministers of his Department had to discuss tax evasion and avoidance between (a) 5 April 2016 and 5 May 2016 and (b) 6 May 2016 and 6 June 2016.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","39934"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523842","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-15","<p>The Government recognises that developing countries may have different preferences from those of the UK and is willing to accommodate these preferences as part of a balanced agreement that is acceptable to both sides.</p><p> </p><p>By governing the taxation of cross-border income flows in a predictable manner and eliminating double taxation and excessive taxation, tax treaties promote international trade and investment, leading to sustainable tax revenues, which are vital in financing for development.</p><p> </p><p>Treasury Ministers decide the UK’s treaty negotiation programme following consultation with a number of interested parties, including the Department for International Development.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","39976","2016-06-15T16:03:00.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523842/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523842/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523842/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-08","Taxation: Developing Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the Government's anti-poverty objectives in (a) Malawi, (b) Ghana and (c) Nepal are being taken into account when negotiating tax treaties with those countries.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","39928"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523843","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-15","<p>National Insurance contributions (NICs) are not intended to tax all forms of income. As a system of social security, the purpose of NICs is that individuals contribute when they are working, in order to build entitlement to contributory benefits such as the State Pension.</p><p> </p><p>Taxes are levied on non-employment income through the rest of the tax system, and the government’s policies since 2010 have repeatedly increased the contribution of the wealthy. The richest fifth of households will contribute more than half (52%) of UK household tax receipts in 2019-20; under the 2010-11 tax system, they would have paid 49%.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-06-15T14:49:13.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523843/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523843/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523843/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-08","National Insurance Contributions: Investment Income","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the distributional effect of the exclusion from National Insurance contributions of property, dividends, pensions and other forms of non-employment income.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","39914"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523844","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-16","<p>The Chair and Board members will be appointed in accordance with the public appointments process. It is expected that the members of the Institute’s board will be comprised primarily of persons with a background as employers and business leaders. This is to ensure that employers continue to drive apprenticeship quality. Applications to join the Institute’s board are also open to representatives of other organisations, including the trade unions.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-06-16T10:16:56.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523844/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523844/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523844/answer","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523844/answer/previousversion/3459","Biography information for Nick Boles","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-08","Institute for Apprenticeships","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what representation there will be on the board of the Institute for Apprenticeships from (a) business, (b) charities and (c) trades unions.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","39895"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523845","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-14","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In June 2016 we will be publishing provisional funding bands, which will set the maximum amount of funding which is available for each apprenticeship, as well as the provisional level of the government support that will be available towards the cost of apprenticeship training if you are not a levy paying employer, from April 2017. The final levels of funding and full, draft funding and eligibility rules will be published in October.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-06-14T12:58:01.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523845/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523845/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523845/answer","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523845/answer/previousversion/3463","Biography information for Nick Gibb","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-08","Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what the funding caps for apprenticeship standards and frameworks will be in the new levy system.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","39896"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523846","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-14","<p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Institute for Apprenticeships will advise on funding rates for all newly developed apprenticeships and, where appropriate, the funding rate for standards and assessment plans when they are reviewed. <br></p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-06-14T12:56:15.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523846/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523846/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523846/answer","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523846/answer/previousversion/3465","Biography information for Nick Boles","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-08","Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, which body will have the responsibility for conducting reviews of the funding caps on apprenticeship standards and frameworks.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","39899"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523847","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-14","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>Provisional funding bands will be published in June 2016, and finalised in October 2016. The Institute for Apprenticeships will play a role in reviewing them once it is operational. The frequency of this will be agreed at that point.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-06-14T12:54:33.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523847/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523847/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523847/answer","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523847/answer/previousversion/3468","Biography information for Nick Boles","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-08","Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how frequently the funding caps on apprenticeship standards and frameworks will be reviewed.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","39900"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523848","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-13","<p>The Treasury does not have a specific definition of the digital economy, and we are unaware of other attempts by Government bodies to create such a definition.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-06-13T13:47:36.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523848/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523848/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523848/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-08","Digital Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 7 June 2016 to Question 905207, what definition of the digital economy is used by (a) his Department, (b) the Office of National Statistics and (c) other government bodies.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","39901"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523849","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-15","<p>The issues raised are a matter for the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), who are operationally independent from Government.</p><p> </p><p>The question has been passed on to the FCA. The FCA will reply directly to the honourable member by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-06-15T14:38:37.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523849/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523849/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523849/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-08","Financial Services: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps his Department is taking to prevent regulated financial intermediaries from promoting products in the unregulated sector by implying that victims of misselling or fraud will have recourse to the protections offered by regulation.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","39907"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523850","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-15","<p>The Government recognises that developing countries may have different preferences from those of the UK and is willing to accommodate these preferences as part of a balanced agreement that is acceptable to both sides.</p><p> </p><p>By governing the taxation of cross-border income flows in a predictable manner and eliminating double taxation and excessive taxation, tax treaties promote international trade and investment, leading to sustainable tax revenues, which are vital in financing for development.</p><p> </p><p>Treasury Ministers decide the UK’s treaty negotiation programme following consultation with a number of interested parties, including the Department for International Development.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","39928","2016-06-15T16:03:00.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523850/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523850/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523850/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-08","Taxation: Developing Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the Department for International Development had any role in the current negotiations of tax treaties with (a) Malawi, (b) Lesotho, (c) Ghana and (d) Nepal.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","39976"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523851","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-20","<p>The destructive cyber attack directed against Sony Pictures Entertainment in November 2015 was condemned at the time by the Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond). The ability of both state and non-state actors to conduct sophisticated cyber attacks is something the UK takes seriously and we have committed to investing £1.9 billion in cyber security over the next 5 years. The Government does not hold information on British nationals involved in the Sony incident.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-06-20T12:40:19.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523851/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523851/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523851/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-08","Neighbourhood Development Plans","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Anelay of St Johns on 5 November 2015 (HL2969), whether the government of the Democratic People’s Republic of Korea’s hacking of Sony Pictures Entertainment, as verified by the United States Federal Bureau of Investigation in December 2014, posed a terrorist threat to British nationals in the United States and the international community.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL540"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523852","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-15","<p>The government is committed to ensuring that members of the public are given the help they need to make informed financial decisions. This is why the government published a paper at Budget - <em>Public Financial Guidance Review: Proposal for Consultation. </em>The paper set out plans to create a new money guidance body which will identify gaps in the financial guidance market and commission targeted debt advice, money guidance and financial capability projects to fill those gaps.</p><p> </p><p>The paper published at Budget sought views on how the new money guidance body should best deliver guidance services. The consultation closed on Wednesday 8 June and the government will publish a response in the Autumn. <strong><br> </strong></p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-06-15T15:22:46.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523852/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523852/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523852/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-08","Financial Services: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what role the new money guidance body will play in coordinating financial capability initiatives.","false","Biography information for Mr Alistair Carmichael","Orkney and Shetland","Mr Alistair Carmichael","40051"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523853","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-21","<p>The Democratic People’s Republic of Korea's (DPRK) arbitrary use of violence against its citizens, as documented in the UN Commission of Inquiry report, underlines the brutality of the regime and its lack of respect for basic human rights. The Government has made clear its concerns about the appalling human rights situation in North Korea, directly with the regime and in international fora, including at the UN General Assembly and the Human Rights Council.</p><p>The DPRK’s flagrant violation of UN Security Council Resolutions and its continuing provocative behaviour is a clear threat to regional stability and international security. The UN Security Council unanimously adopted Resolution 2270 on 2 March 2016 in response to the DPRK’s nuclear test of 6 January and satellite launch, using ballistic technology, of 7 February. The EU has implemented additional measures.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-06-21T13:35:10.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523853/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523853/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523853/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-08","Government Departments: Contracts for Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the allegations of violence by the Democratic People’s Republic of Korea’s against its citizens, and its use of threats to the international community for the purpose of advancing its political cause.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL541"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523854","Department for Transport","false","2016-06-17","<p>My Hon Friend, the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Transport, Claire Perry MP, as Rail Minister, chairs a monthly meeting with Network Rail, train operators in the South East, Transport Focus, and Department for Transport officials. This group monitors performance and passenger experience and it is absolutely committed to identifying improvements and ensuring rail passengers see the benefits of these improvements being delivered. Network Rail and Southeastern both need to show much greater improvement in their ability to fix faults quickly and communicate with their passengers more effectively. The Department will ensure that lessons are learned from the disruption in Kent that day.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-06-17T10:31:39.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523854/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523854/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523854/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-06-08","Government Departments: Contracts for Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the disruption to rail passengers in Kent on 6 June, what action they are taking to ensure a more reliable service for rail passengers travelling between Kent and London terminals.","false","Biography information for Lord Condon",,"Lord Condon","HL542"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523855","Home Office","false","2016-06-16","<p>The Home Office does not collect this information. Decisions on the local deployment of assets and resources, including marine units, are for individual chief constables working with their police and crime commissioner.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-06-16T14:52:33.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523855/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523855/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523855/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-06-08","Government Departments: Consultants","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government which police forces in areas with North Sea coastlines or English Channel coastlines from Norfolk south and west to Devon and Cornwall have marine or boat units capable of patrolling estuaries or inshore sea waters; and what is the maximum range in which those police forces' units are licensed to operate.","false","Biography information for Lord Condon",,"Lord Condon","HL543"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523856","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-06-20","<p>There are no official emissions estimates available for recent years for many developing countries, including India and China. One widely used 3<sup>rd</sup> party estimate is however available from the World Resources Institute CAIT dataset.</p><p> </p><p>This data suggests that in 2012, the latest available year, China’s domestic greenhouse gas emissions (including land use, land use change and forestry, but excluding international aviation and shipping ) accounted for around 22% of the global total (25% for CO<sub>2</sub> only).</p><p> </p><p>India’s domestic greenhouse gas emissions (including land use, land use change and forestry, but excluding international aviation and shipping) accounted for around 6% of the global total (5% for CO<sub>2</sub> only).</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-06-20T16:21:32.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523856/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523856/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523856/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-08","Welsh Government","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what percentage of world atmospheric carbon dioxide emissions China and India contributed in the latest period for which records are available.","false","Biography information for Lord Donoughue",,"Lord Donoughue","HL544"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523857","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-22","<p>The Scotland Act 2014 permits the Scottish Government to borrow up to £2.2 billion for capital purposes and £0.5 billion to cover shortfalls in cash receipts. The Scotland Act 2016 provides for these to be revised in due course to £3bn and £1.75bn respectively.</p><p> </p><p>The Welsh Government may borrow up to £500 million to cover shortfalls in the Welsh Consolidated Fund as set out in the Government of Wales Act 2006. The Wales Act 2014 confers aggregate capital borrowing powers of up to £500 million on the Welsh Government. In response to a specific request from the Welsh Government, the Government has also provided early access to these capital borrowing powers in order to support the delivery of the M4 relief road.</p><p> </p><p>The Northern Ireland Executive has a statutory borrowing limit of £3 billion for capital purposes as set out in the Northern Ireland (Loans) Act 1975 as amended by the Northern Ireland (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2006. The Northern Ireland Executive may borrow up to £250 million to cover shortfalls in the Northern Ireland Consolidated Fund as set out in the Northern Ireland Act 1998.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","HL547","2016-06-22T11:13:23.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523857/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523857/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523857/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-08","Political Parties: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what are the current borrowing limits imposed on (1) the Scottish Parliament, (2) the National Assembly for Wales, and (3) the Northern Ireland Assembly.","false","Biography information for Lord Empey",,"Lord Empey","HL545"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523858","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-15","<p>The 2015 Spending Review confirmed a historic four year settlement for local government, including making councils responsible to local people for their financing, rather than central government. It delivers a long-held ambition for councils to be financed from locally raised resources. And it means that by the end of this Parliament, councils will benefit from 100 per cent business rates retention – something they have been calling for, for over a quarter of a century.</p><p>It is a settlement which has been subject to extensive consultation, including with the Local Government Association, which welcomed the offer of a four year planning horizon. A range of additional funding flexibilities were sought during the consultation, especially on fees for planning and licensing.</p><p>In February 2016, proposals were outlined to link future increases in councils’ fees for processing planning applications to performance in terms of speed and quality of decisions.</p><p>By the end of this Parliament, local government will be able to retain 100 per cent of local taxes, including up to £13 billion of revenue from business rates, to spend on local government services. In order to ensure that the reforms are fiscally neutral, these new powers must come with new responsibilities, as well as phasing out grants from Whitehall. The government is working closely with the Local Government Association to design the reforms.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-06-15T15:29:32.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523858/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523858/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523858/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-06-08","Local Government Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what discussions he has had with the Local Government Association on the effect of charges on local authorities of changes to funding over the next five years announced in the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","39883"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523859","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-21","<p>Treasury Ministers are in regular contact with Devolved Administration Ministers on a variety of matters.</p><p> </p><p>Each of the Devolved Administrations has a range of capital and resource borrowing powers set out in legislation.</p><p> </p><p>In addition to these, the Stormont House Agreement provided flexibility to use £700m of capital borrowing to fund a voluntary exit scheme over a period of 4 years with £200m in 2015-16, £200m in 2016-17, £200m in 2017-18 and £100m in 2018-19 as well as up to an additional £350m borrowing for infrastructure projects with a profile over four years with £100m in 2015-16, £100m in 2016-17, £100m in 2017-18 and £50m in 2018-19.</p><p> </p><p>The Fresh Start Agreement and Implementation Plan provided assurances that the NI Executive could access the full amount of additional borrowing provided by the Stormont House Agreement even if it is able to realise agreed efficiency savings from Voluntary Exit Scheme without switching the full amount of existing borrowing for that purpose.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is working closely with the Northern Ireland Executive to implement the Fresh Start Agreement.</p><p> </p><p>In response to a specific request from the Welsh Government, the Government has provided early access to the capital borrowing powers in the Wales Act 2014 in order to support the delivery of the M4 relief road.</p><p> </p><p>Again, the Government is working closely with the Welsh Government on this matter.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2016-06-21T12:55:27.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523859/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523859/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523859/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-08","Fisheries Convention","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether any requests have been received from the devolved administrations to raise their borrowing limits; and if so, what increases were requested, when such requests were made, and whether any have been agreed to.","false","Biography information for Lord Empey",,"Lord Empey","HL546"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523860","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-15","<p>The Secretary of State has had no formal meetings with his counterpart in the Northern Ireland Executive.</p><p>However, the Department is actively involved with the British Irish Council, who meet frequently to discuss cross-cutting housing issues and share expertise.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-06-15T15:27:35.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523860/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523860/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523860/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-06-08","First Time Buyers: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what discussions he has had with his counterpart in the Northern Ireland Executive on steps to support first-time buyers.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","39884"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523861","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-22","<p>The Scotland Act 2014 permits the Scottish Government to borrow up to £2.2 billion for capital purposes and £0.5 billion to cover shortfalls in cash receipts. The Scotland Act 2016 provides for these to be revised in due course to £3bn and £1.75bn respectively.</p><p> </p><p>The Welsh Government may borrow up to £500 million to cover shortfalls in the Welsh Consolidated Fund as set out in the Government of Wales Act 2006. The Wales Act 2014 confers aggregate capital borrowing powers of up to £500 million on the Welsh Government. In response to a specific request from the Welsh Government, the Government has also provided early access to these capital borrowing powers in order to support the delivery of the M4 relief road.</p><p> </p><p>The Northern Ireland Executive has a statutory borrowing limit of £3 billion for capital purposes as set out in the Northern Ireland (Loans) Act 1975 as amended by the Northern Ireland (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 2006. The Northern Ireland Executive may borrow up to £250 million to cover shortfalls in the Northern Ireland Consolidated Fund as set out in the Northern Ireland Act 1998.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","HL545","2016-06-22T11:13:23.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523861/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523861/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523861/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-08","Fisheries Convention","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they permit the devolved administrations in the UK to borrow money for resource budget purposes.","false","Biography information for Lord Empey",,"Lord Empey","HL547"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523862","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-15","<p>One person without a home is one too many. That is why we have increased central investment to tackle homelessness over the next four years to £139 million. This includes a new national £10 million programme to support innovative ways to prevent and reduce rough sleeping, building on the success of our No Second Night Out initiative.</p><p>Homelessness is a devolved matter. I have not had any conversations with my counterpart in the Northern Ireland Executive but would be happy to do so.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-06-15T15:30:13.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523862/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523862/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523862/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-06-08","Sleeping Rough: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what discussions he has had with his counterpart in the Northern Ireland Executive on reducing the number of people sleeping rough in the UK.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","39886"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523863","Department for Education","false","2016-06-15","<p>During the last 12 months, the fraud allegations at the Haberdashers’ Aske’s Federation academy trust chain have been reviewed as a criminal investigation since first reported to the police in October 2012 by this multi-academy trust. The criminal case against the perpetrator of the fraud began week commencing 6 June at Woolwich Crown Court.</p><p> </p><p>The Education Funding Agency (EFA) has engaged with the Trust from the outset and immediately requested that the Trust assess financial systems and risks. The Trust carried out an independent and thorough review of its internal control procedures and reported on this to the EFA. The Trust has taken all the appropriate action since the issue was first identified and the remaining key actions now rest with the Police and the Crown Prosecution Service.</p><p> </p><p>Academies and free schools face tighter financial scrutiny than local authority maintained schools. They must publish annual, independently-audited accounts, of which there is no equivalent requirement on maintained schools. We take swift action whenever we identify financial irregularities.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-06-15T12:21:23.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523863/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523863/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523863/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-06-08","Fisheries Convention","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what action, if any, they have taken during the last 12 months in relation to the fraud allegations at the Haberdashers' Aske's Federation academy chain.","false","Biography information for Lord Grocott",,"Lord Grocott","HL548"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523865","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-21","<p>I refer the Noble Lord to the statement given by my Noble Friend Lord Gardiner of Kimble on 10 December 2015.</p>",,"Baroness Evans of Bowes Park",,"2016-06-21T16:08:33.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523865/answer","Biography information for Baroness Evans of Bowes Park","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523865/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523865/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-08","Fisheries Convention","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to continue the Official History Programme; and if so, how.","false","Biography information for Lord Lexden",,"Lord Lexden","HL549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523866","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-21","<p>The Government is committed to facilitating pre-legislative scrutiny when it is possible to do so. In the last session five draft Bills or packages of draft legislation were published. Announcements will be made in due course about draft legislation to be published in the current session.</p>",,"Baroness Evans of Bowes Park",,"2016-06-21T16:08:01.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523866/answer","Biography information for Baroness Evans of Bowes Park","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523866/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523866/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-08","Community Housing Fund","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many of the measures announced in the Queen's Speech will be published in draft and subject to pre-legislative scrutiny.","false","Biography information for Lord Lisvane",,"Lord Lisvane","HL550"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523867","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-06-17","<p>Consideration was given to include TV licencing in the Tell Us Once Service, however as the Department for Work and Pensions already provides this information to the Department for Culture, Media and Sport, it is not necessary to also include it in the Tell Us Once Service.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-06-17T13:54:27.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523867/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523867/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523867/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-06-08","Television: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, for what reasons TV Licensing is not included in the Tell Us Once service.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","39908"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523868","Department for Education","false","2016-06-29","<p>Local authorities have a duty under the Childcare Act 2006 to ensure sufficient children’s centres to meet the needs of local families. Local authorities must also consult fully before any significant changes are made to children’s centre services.</p><p>All 27 county councils in England have children’s centre sites open to families and children providing children's centre services as part of a network.</p><p>According to data supplied to the department by local authorities, at end May 2016, eight county councils had closed some sites within their children’s centre networks.</p><p>An independent survey carried out by the national children’s charity, 4Children (published October 2015) estimated more than a million children and families were using children’s centres.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-06-29T14:36:31.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523868/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523868/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523868/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-06-08","Roads: Accidents","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many county councils have closed down their children's centres.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL551"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523869","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-13","<p>The English Heritage Trust flies its house flag at its historic sites to help visitors identify its properties. Where properties have more than one flagpole, they are encouraged to fly the Union flag. On certain important occasions, including on the birthday of Her Majesty the Queen (21 April) and Remembrance Day, the Union flag is flown from all sites with flagpoles.</p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett",,"2016-06-13T14:18:58.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523869/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523869/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523869/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-06-08","Historic Buildings: Flags","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will take steps to ensure that landmarks in the stewardship of English Heritage fly the Union flag in place of the organisation's house flag.","false","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","39881"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523870","Department of Health","false","2016-06-15","<p>We recognise that better provision of defibrillators and increasing the number of people trained in cardiopulmonary resuscitation could help save more lives of those who have a cardiac arrest outside a hospital setting.</p><p> </p><p>That is why the Chancellor announced in the budget in March 2016 that the Government is making available another £1 million to make public access defibrillators and coronary pulmonary resuscitation training more widely available in communities across England. This builds on last year’s funding of £1 million, which provided almost 700 more publicly accessible defibrillators in communities across England and increased the numbers of people trained in cardiopulmonary resuscitation.</p><p> </p><p>Details on how this second tranche of the funding can be accessed will be available in due course.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Education (DfE) is encouraging schools to purchase automated external defibrillators (AEDs) as part of their first aid equipment and in November 2014 announced new arrangements to allow schools to purchase AEDs at a competitive price. This is the result of a unique agreement between the DfE and the Department of Health in which devices are bought in bulk and the savings of around 50% are passed on to schools. Since the launch of this policy, 1,389 defibrillators have been provided to schools.</p><p> </p><p>To help schools in considering whether to purchase a defibrillator, DfE has published advice on installing and maintaining AEDs on school premises. This has been developed drawing on the expertise of National Health Service ambulance services and voluntary and community sector organisations.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-06-15T12:22:50.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523870/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523870/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523870/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-08","Trade Promotion","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their policy on providing defibrillators in public places and schools.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL552"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523871","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-14","<p>TV Licensing (TVL) should be notified when a licence fee holder dies. If the person making the notice has previously been covered by the licence, it will be transferred into their name. If an executor or family member notifies TVL that a property is now vacant, the licence is cancelled, and a refund is made to the deceased’s estate.</p><p>In the case of an over-75s licence, TVL is informed by the Department of Work and Pensions of deaths of those aged over 75. In this case, TVL will write to the licensed address to inform anyone living with the deceased that the licence will cover the occupants until the licence term expires.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-06-14T10:50:52.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523871/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523871/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523871/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-06-08","Television: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate he has made of the amount charged to the deceased by TV Licensing in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","39915"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523872","Department for International Development","false","2016-06-20","<p>The UK is supporting the Governments of Jordan and Lebanon to deliver the landmark commitments made at the London Syria Conference to enable every refugee and vulnerable host community child to access education by the end of the 2016/2017 school year. UK funding will be aligned with the plans of partner governments and a range of delivery mechanisms are being considered. Our approach is not exclusive: programmes will be implemented through partners who can deliver increases in access to quality education, quickly, efficiently and at scale.</p><p>The UK has worked with NGOs and voluntary organisations to provide support in both Jordan and Lebanon and will consider partnering with those that can demonstrate the ability to deliver effective results in line with Government strategies, progress towards the London Conference goals and offer value for money.</p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2016-06-20T12:26:57.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523872/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523872/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523872/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-06-08","Pupils: Mental Health","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the UK funding available to support refugee children in state schools in Jordan and Lebanon can also be made available to voluntary organisations for the same purpose.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL553"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523873","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-06-13","<p>We are currently reviewing the strategic approach, to support citizens in the wider bereavement journey to support the Government’s 2020 vision and the better use of data across government. This review will include the Tell Us Once Service and the Department for Culture Media and Sport.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-06-13T14:57:05.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523873/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523873/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523873/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-06-08","Television: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will develop plans to include TV Licensing in the Tell Us Once service.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","39920"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523874","Department for International Development","false","2016-06-20","<p>The UK Government is aware of the survey by the American University of Beirut and the United Nations Relief and Works Agency (UNRWA). DFID staff attended the survey’s launch event and have noted its findings.</p><p>The UK is a long-term supporter of UNRWA, including in Lebanon, providing over £60 million in 2015/16 and remaining the third largest donor to the UNRWA General Fund. We also provided £12m in total to UNRWA in Lebanon through the 2015 and 2016 Syria Emergency Appeals, and £1.9m this year through the UK Conflict Stability and Security Fund, supporting Palestinian youth with vocational and English skills training and job placement.</p><p>DFID has also committed to spending up to £40m a year on education in Lebanon, with a major programming element aimed at providing non-formal education to the most vulnerable children and youth, including Palestinians.</p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2016-06-20T12:26:04.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523874/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523874/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523874/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-06-08","Pupils: Mental Health","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the recent survey by the American University of Beirut and UNRWA on the socioeconomic status of Palestinian refugees in Lebanon; and what bilateral and multilateral action they are taking to meet the challenges identified by that survey.","false","Biography information for Lord Judd",,"Lord Judd","HL554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523875","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-13","<table><tbody><tr><td colspan="6" rowspan="5"><p>The information on more than 19 vehicle types used over 13 years of both Operation Herrick and Operation Telic is not held centrally and could be provided only at disapproportionate cost.</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-06-13T16:24:08.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523875/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523875/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523875/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-08","Armed Forces: Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many and what proportion of each type of vehicle procured as part of urgent operational requirements for (a) Operation Herrick and (b) Operation Telic have been returned to the UK.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","39947"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523876","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-06-20","<p>The regulations for the revised EU Milk Scheme come into force this month and will apply from 1 August 2017. Detailed rules for implementing the scheme and for the drawing up of national strategies are now being negotiated. We will use this period to consider the new requirements and expect to start consultation with interested parties this autumn.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2016-06-20T13:48:30.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523876/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523876/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523876/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-06-08","Patients: Telephones","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to develop a strategy for implementing the revised European School Milk Scheme by September 2017.","false","Biography information for Lord Lexden",,"Lord Lexden","HL555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523877","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-13","<p>The numbers of Jackal reconnaissance and Foxhound protected patrol vehicles in use with the Army in each of the last six years are shown in the table below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Jackal</p></td><td><p>Foxhound</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-2016</p></td><td><p>441</p></td><td><p>400</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-2015</p></td><td><p>441</p></td><td><p>400</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-2014</p></td><td><p>441</p></td><td><p>400</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-2013</p></td><td><p>441-502</p></td><td><p>216</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-2012</p></td><td><p>441-502</p></td><td><p>216</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-2011</p></td><td><p>502</p></td><td><p>12</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Fleet size numbers are assessed as at 1 April each year. There were 61 Jackals damaged beyond economic repair between 1 April 2011 and 31 March.</p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-06-13T16:23:12.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523877/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523877/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523877/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-08","Armoured Fighting Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many (a) Jackal and (b) Foxhound patrol vehicles were in use by the Army in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","39948"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523878","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-14","<p>Our records before 2010 do not show whether an officer joined the Diplomatic Service as a Fast Streamer. However, we have confirmed that all but eight of the 165 Fast Streamers who have joined the Diplomatic Service since 2010, are either still working in the Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO); are on loan to another department; or are currently on special unpaid leave and are expected to return to the FCO in due course.</p><p>This would be equivalent to an attrition rate of around 5 per cent over five years.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-06-14T15:00:09.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523878/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523878/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523878/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-08","Mental Health Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what have been the retention rates of Civil Service Fast Streamers in the Diplomatic Service since 2000.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL556"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523879","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-21","<p>We are aware of reports, including from Amnesty International on 6 June, of the alleged use of cluster munitions in the Saudi-led Coalition campaign in Yemen. The Government takes such allegations very seriously. We are analysing the case and seeking clarification from the Saudi-led Coalition.</p><p>We have raised this issue with the Saudi Arabian authorities and, in line with our obligations under the Convention on Cluster Munitions, we continue to encourage Saudi Arabia, as a non-party to the Convention, to accede to it. The UK last provided cluster munitions to Saudi Arabia nearly 30 years ago; the final delivery was in 1989.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-06-21T16:01:59.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523879/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523879/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523879/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-08","Terrorism: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what conclusions they have reached following their investigations into the allegations that British-made cluster munitions have been used by Saudi Arabia during the conflict in Yemen.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL557"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523880","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-14","<p>There is no retirement age for Royal Fleet Auxiliary employees. I can provide the following numbers of those personnel who were aged 60 or Over on final date of service:</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2008-09</p></td><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>2015-16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>20</p></td><td><p>15</p></td><td><p>20</p></td><td><p>20</p></td><td><p>20</p></td><td><p>30</p></td><td><p>35</p></td><td><p>30</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>All totals are rounded in accordance with the Defence Statistics rounding policy.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-06-14T15:54:16.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523880/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523880/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523880/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-08","Royal Fleet Auxiliary","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many merchant seafarers employed by the Royal Fleet Auxiliary have retired in each year since 2008-09.","false","Biography information for Ian Mearns","Gateshead","Ian Mearns","39970"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523881","Home Office","false","2016-06-16","<p>Border Force is committed to operating three cutters in UK waters at any given time. We currently have a total of four available for use in UK waters, with one rotated into use where required. These figures only include the number of cutters currently deployed in UK territorial waters and do not include the additional military and law enforcement vessels available. Border Force takes a multi-layered approach to maritime security; using a combination of cutters, radar and aerial surveillance to detect efforts to smuggle guns and drugs or facilitate illegal entry into the country. They also work closely with domestic and international partners on an intelligence-led approach, allowing us to tackle the criminals involved before they leave for the UK. Border Force is also investing in a new fleet of rigid hull inflatable boats (RHIBS) as part of a new maritime security strategy. The vessels will patrol the UK coast, helping to intercept attempts to smuggle migrants, drugs and dangerous weapons into the country.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-06-16T14:55:48.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523881/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523881/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523881/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-06-08","Community Development","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many Border Force vessels patrol UK territorial waters at any one time; and how many are needed to ensure the required levels of surveillance and security of the UK's coastline.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL558"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523882","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-15","<p>The Royal Navy (RN) has a Memorandum of Understanding (MOU) with the Maritime and Coastguard Agency (MCA) to allow Warfare Officers to obtain commercial Standards of Training, Certification and Watchkeeping (STCW) certificates of competency. Discussions with the MCA have commenced to develop a similar MOU for Engineer Officers and Ratings. More widely the RN continues to seek to align its training with STCW requirements. The RN Resettlement Service also offers impartial advice on second careers with many strong links with maritime sector organisations and companies.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-06-15T14:06:38.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523882/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523882/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523882/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-08","Shipping","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps his Department has taken to implement recommendation 15 of the Department for Transport's Maritime Growth Study, published in September 2015, on improving links between the Royal Navy and the wider UK maritime sector.","false","Biography information for Ian Mearns","Gateshead","Ian Mearns","39966"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523883","Home Office","false","2016-06-16","<p>Specific details on numbers or locations of suspected illegal maritime arrivals are not disclosed for security reasons.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-06-16T14:54:06.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523883/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523883/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523883/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-06-08","Immigration","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many illegal maritime arrivals have reached the UK in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL559"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523884","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-22","<table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2" rowspan="5"><p> </p></td><td colspan="6" rowspan="5"><p>I refer my noble Friend to the answer given by my hon. Friend the Minister of State for Defence Procurement (Mr Philip Dunne) in the House of Commons on 6 June 2016, to Question number 38719.</p><p>On the question of any impact on the capacity and efficacy of the Royal Navy, the Type 45 destroyers are hugely capable ships. They have consistently made a difference to our safety and security, and continue to make an enormous contribution to the defence of the UK and our international partners.</p></td></tr></tbody></table>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-06-22T11:17:04.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523884/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523884/answer","Hansard Extract 6 June 2016 HOC38719.docx","Hansard Extract 6 June 2016 HOC38719.docx","Type 45 Destroyers","Type 45 Destroyers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523884/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-08","Immigration","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government who is responsible for (1) the reported design flaw in the engines of the Type 45 destroyers, and (2) the costs of the refit in the light of those flaws; and what assessment they have made of the impact of that design flaw on the capacity and efficacy of the Royal Navy.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL560"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523885","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-15","<p>The Ministry of Defence does not capture and report data on hourly earnings, and therefore does not provide comparative data in this way.</p><p>The Department has recently published an Equal Pay Audit 2015 report which can be found at the following address:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/mod-equal-pay-audit-report-2015</p><p>This Audit presents a comparison of male to female and White to Black, Asian and Minority Ethnic (BAME) annualised average salaries in the period 1 October 2014 to 1 October 2015. This meets the Department's obligations under the Public Sector Equality Duty to provide information on its workforce identified by the Equality Act 2010.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-06-15T14:03:26.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523885/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523885/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523885/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-08","Ministry of Defence: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 26 May 2016 to Question 38217, on his Department's BME pay gap, where the information about this is held; and what estimate he has made of the cost of providing the information.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","39973"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523886","Attorney General","false","2016-06-21","In all cases decisions to investigate are made by the Director of the Serious Fraud Office, who acts independently. In respect of BHS, the SFO has confirmed that it is reviewing material in its possession. If the Director considers there are reasonable grounds to suspect serious or complex fraud which meets his Statement of Principle, he will open a formal criminal investigation.",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2016-06-21T12:52:35.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523886/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523886/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523886/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-06-08","Games","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have asked the Serious Fraud Office to investigate matters related to the sale and purchase of BHS.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL561"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523887","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-14","<p>The Royal Fleet Auxiliary (RFA) recruits and trains UK Merchant Seafarers for service with the RFA. The RFA as one of the largest trainers of UK seafarers is fully engaged with the UK Chamber of Shipping and Merchant Navy Training Board in shaping the current and future training requirements of seafarers. The RFA as part of the wider Naval Service is represented at the Ministerial Working Groups for the Maritime Growth Study by the Royal Navy.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-06-14T15:53:34.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523887/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523887/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523887/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-08","Shipping","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what discussions he has had with his Ministerial colleagues on the potential effect of the recommendations of the Maritime Growth Study, published in September 2015, on the future supply of UK-domiciled merchant seafarers to the Royal Fleet Auxiliary.","false","Biography information for Ian Mearns","Gateshead","Ian Mearns","39967"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523888","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-22","<p>I refer the noble Lord to the answers I gave him on 11 April 2016 to Question HL7227 and on 9 May to Question HL7900.</p><p>We have published details of savings made through efficiency and reform each year since 2010-11. The most recent report can be found on www.gov.uk.</p>",,"Baroness Evans of Bowes Park",,"2016-06-22T15:48:13.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523888/answer","Biography information for Baroness Evans of Bowes Park","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523888/answer","HL562 Attachment 1.pdf ; HL562 Attachment 2.pdf ; HL562 Attachment 3.pdf","HL562 Attachment 1.pdf ; HL562 Attachment 2.pdf ; HL562 Attachment 3.pdf","Attachment 1 ; Attachment 2 ; Attachment 3","Attachment 1 ; Attachment 2 ; Attachment 3","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523888/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-08","Games","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to publish the savings in public sector procurement as a result of following the advice of Sir Philip Green; and whether they will consider inviting Sir Philip to review the adequacy and effectiveness of implementation.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL562"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523889","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-27","<p>The Type 26 Global Combat Ship will be designed for joint and multinational operations from the tropics and Arabian Gulf in the summer to the sub-Arctic. The ship's design will accommodate a broad range of environmental conditions to deliver a globally deployable ship throughout its planned life.</p><p>I am withholding further detail as disclosure would, or would be likely to, prejudice the capability, effectiveness or security of the Armed Forces.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-06-27T15:43:44.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523889/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523889/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523889/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-08","Type 26 Frigates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps he is taking to ensure that the Type 26 frigate will be able to operate across the full range of climatic conditions in which the Royal Navy operates.","false","Biography information for Mrs Flick Drummond","Portsmouth South","Mrs Flick Drummond","39921"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523890","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-06-20","<p>Three Capacity Market auctions have been held so far. Two market-wide, four-year ahead (T4) auctions were held in December 2014 (for delivery in 2018/19) and December 2015 (for 2019/20), clearing at £19.40/kW and £18.00/kW respectively, and securing 49.3GW and 46.4GW of capacity for delivery in those years. A smaller-scale Transitional Arrangements auction, focused solely on the Demand Side Response (DSR) sector, was held in January 2016, securing 803MW of DSR for 2016/17 at a clearing price of £27.50/kW. Winning bidders obtain Capacity Market Agreements, whose terms are established in law by the Capacity Market regulations and rules. Winning bidders and the volume of their individual agreements are published on National Grid’s CM register.</p><p> </p><p>Results for the three auctions held so far are attached.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-06-20T15:24:10.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523890/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523890/answer","T-4 2014 Final Auction Results Report.pdf ; T-4 Final Results 2015.pdf ; Transitional Auction 2016 - Final Results.pdf","T-4 2014 Final Auction Results Report.pdf ; T-4 Final Results 2015.pdf ; Transitional Auction 2016 - Final Results.pdf","T4 2014 Final Auction results ; T4 2015 Final Auction results ; Transitional auction 2016 - final results","T4 2014 Final Auction results ; T4 2015 Final Auction results ; Transitional auction 2016 - final results","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523890/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-08","Brexit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what Capacity Market auctions have been held to date under the Energy Act 2013, and what were the price and terms of the successful bids at each auction.","false","Biography information for Lord Rowlands",,"Lord Rowlands","HL563"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523891","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-16","<p>Representatives of the Department meet AeroVironment representatives on a regular basis to discuss current and potential future capabilities, and the Department is aware of the capabilities of the Blackwing Reconnaissance System. However, the Department has no capability requirement to procure an underwater launched Unmanned Aerial System at this stage, and, as such, there have not been any formal discussions with AeroVironment on a possible procurement of Blackwing.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","39912","2016-06-16T16:29:46.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523891/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523891/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523891/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-08","Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether his Department has considered purchasing the AeroVironment Blackwing miniature tube-launched drone.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","39911"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523892","Department for International Development","false","2016-06-20","<p>We are seeking to establish commercial air services using the southern approach to the runway where wind shear is not a significant issue. A number of aircraft types have been identified which should offer reasonable performance using a southern approach (the Airbus A318 and A319, Boeing 737-600 and 737-700). We are in discussions with airlines on how we can bring one of these into service.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2016-06-20T16:21:58.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523892/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523892/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523892/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-06-08","Students: Loans","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answer by Baroness Verma on 7 June (HL Deb, col 663), what is meant by the phrase "depend on securing the right aircraft".","false","Biography information for Lord Soley",,"Lord Soley","HL564"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523893","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-16","<p>Representatives of the Department meet AeroVironment representatives on a regular basis to discuss current and potential future capabilities, and the Department is aware of the capabilities of the Blackwing Reconnaissance System. However, the Department has no capability requirement to procure an underwater launched Unmanned Aerial System at this stage, and, as such, there have not been any formal discussions with AeroVironment on a possible procurement of Blackwing.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","39911","2016-06-16T16:29:46.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523893/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523893/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523893/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-08","Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether his Department has met representatives of AeroVironment to discuss the Blackwing miniature tube-launched drone.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","39912"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523894","Department for Education","false","2016-06-15","<p>The Government is committed to safeguarding all children and protecting them from the risk of harm and extremism, including in out-of-school settings.</p><p> </p><p>The Prime Minister announced plans to introduce a new system of oversight for out-of-school education settings – such as supplementary schools and tuition centres – which teach children intensively, on 7 October 2015. These were confirmed in the Government’s Counter-Extremism Strategy which was published on 19 October. These plans to regulate out-of-school settings which teach children intensively were set out in the call for evidence which ran for 6 and a half weeks between 26 November and 11 January.</p><p> </p><p>We are not proposing to regulate settings teaching children for a short period every week, such as Sunday schools or the Scouts, or one-off residential activities, such as a week-long summer camp. We are looking specifically at settings providing intensive education outside school where children could be spending more than six hours a week.</p><p> </p><p>The call for evidence sought views on the appropriateness of seeking to prohibit teaching which undermines or is incompatible with fundamental British values. Now that the call for evidence has closed, we are considering carefully the responses received as we develop the proposals further.</p><p>We will be publishing our response to the call for evidence and setting out the next steps on the proposals in due course.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-06-15T12:18:41.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523894/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523894/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/523894/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-06-08","Students: Loans","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to require Ofsted inspectors to judge whether the work of mainstream Christian churches with young people, either directly or through approved Christian organisations which specialise in working with young people, in activities such as holiday Bible clubs, church weekends, and summer camps, is in accordance with a "British Values" test; and if so, when such plans would be introduced.","false","Biography information for Lord Mawhinney",,"Lord Mawhinney","HL565"
